<FIRST>r w PM-Budget-Darman Bjt   02-25 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget-Darman, Bjt,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Darman Says Administration Has Specifics on Domestic Cuts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Budget director Richard Darman says the Bush
administration is ready to provide specific details being demanded
by Congress on President Bush's budget as part of the negotiation
process the administration is trying to get started.
   Darman told reporters Friday that the administration has a
position on the proper spending level for ``almost every one'' of
the programs in the $136 billion collection of government agencies
for which the administration is seeking savings of $10 billion.
   Democratic critics have charged that the administration purposely
has left the savings in this area of non-defense programs
unspecified so that Congress will have to take the political heat
for cutting popular domestic programs.
   Darman, however, denied this assertion and said that once the
private negotiations with Congress get under way in earnest, the
administration will be willing to state what its position is.
   ``In order to get the process moving, we will have to take an
initial position,'' Darman said.
   Democrats in Congress have insisted that they want the White
House to put more details about Bush's budget on the record before
they enter into negotiations.
   But Darman said he believed this debate will soon move beyond a
call for more specifics into serious negotiations with congressional
leaders. He predicted those negotiations would start within the next
two weeks.
   ``In a context where a lot of (financial) market players and
other observers are nervous, it is foolish to do business as
usual,'' he said in an hour-long meeting with reporters.
   ``I think it will be virtually guaranteed that we will start a
process that is helpful, above and beyond the normal legislative
process,'' Darman said.
   Darman met again Friday with top Democrats and Republicans from
the congressional budget committees as part of a series of sessions
in which lawmakers have been seeking specific figures about the
spending Bush proposes.
   In the meeting with reporters, Darman rejected the argument that
Bush's $1.16 trillion budget was based on a strategy that will allow
Bush to take credit for popular spending increases and blame
Congress for the painful cuts needed to meet the 1990 deficit target
of $100 billion. The administration estimates the deficit in the
current fiscal year will be $170 billion.
   Taking note of the decision by the Federal Reserve Board to boost
its discount rate Friday to 7 percent, Darman said the action should
prod both congressional leaders and the administration to enter into
serious negotiations to calm fears in financial markets of a
stalemate that would keep federal borrowing demands from declining.
   In Congress, Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., chairman of the House
Budget Committee, agreed.
   Panetta said the discount rate increase should serve as a
``wake-up call'' to lawmakers and administration officials, showing
the ``urgency of the need to cut out the political gamesmanship and
adopt a bold and realistic budget plan.''
   Darman disputed an argument advanced by Senate Budget Committee
chairman, Sen. James Sasser, D-Tenn., that Democrats who support
higher domestic spending than in the Bush budget might be better off
simply allowing across-the-board spending cuts to take effect.
   These spending cuts would be triggered if Congress and the
administration fail to agree on a budget with a deficit of $100
billion. Sasser said earlier this week that the automatic cuts would
result in spending about $10 billion less than Bush wants for the
military and about $10 billion more for domestic programs.
   However, Darman gave out projections from the Bush budget office
showing that discretionary domestic spending would be $4.1 billion
higher under the Bush budget than if the spending cuts take effect
while defense spending would be $15.1 billion below the level in the
Bush budget.
   ``Everybody recognizes that (automatic cuts) are highly
undesirable from the standpoint of defense and national security,''
Darman said.
</TEXT>
