<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 0219EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-NuclearCleanup     02-25 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Cleanup,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Department Admits Flaws in Nuclear Cleanup Study</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department has acknowledged publicly
for the first time that it misjudged both the cost and relative
urgency of hazardous waste cleanup requirements at its 15 nuclear
weapons plants.
   The miscalculations stemmed from a partially flawed computer
model the department used to decide which of 156 environmental
problems at the plants were most severe, Ray Berube, the deputy
assistant secretary for environment, said Friday.
   He told a House Armed Services subcommittee the cleanup will
likely exceed the official $63 billion, and the ranking of hazards
will have to be revised. The rankings are important because they
help determine the timing and scope of environmental cleanup at the
various sites, which are owned by the Energy Department.
   He said the Rocky Flats weapons plant near Golden, Colo., which
was judged the most urgent priority for environmental cleanup in the
preliminary December report, probably will get a lower ranking when
the final survey is completed later this year. He did not say which
site might replace Rocky Flats at the top of the list.
   He also did not say by how much the cleanup cost at the 12-state
nuclear weapons complex would exceed $63 billion.
   Berube said the errors were caused in part by haste, since his
agency decided to speed up its orginal timetable for assessing the
environmental problems because of public pressure to explain how the
wastes would be cleaned up.
   ``We did not have the time to subject that (computer) model to a
public review,'' Berube said. ``I wish we had. The model does need
some improvements.''
   The department says none of the waste _ including toxic organic
compounds such as methylene chloride and radioactive gases such as
tritium _ poses a threat to public health and safety, but that it
might if it is not cleaned up soon.
   An environmental organization, the Natural Resources Defense
Council, testified at the House hearing that the computer model was
``riddled with flaws'' and that in some cases the department made up
data used in the model when the information was not readily
available.
   Jim Werner, an engineer with the council, said the computer model
was ``incapable of indicating which environmental problems should be
addressed in the next few years compared to those that will need
attention several decades from now.''
   ``Given the serious flaws in DOE's rankings, the department's
proposed cleanup budget is also highly suspect,'' said Dan W.
Reicher, an attorney for the environmental group.
   Berube said it was not yet possible for the department to make a
firm estimate of cleanup costs for the weapons plants because not
enough is known about the extent of damage to the environment caused
by four decades of bomb making.
   ``There's a strong chance that these costs will go higher'' than
$63 billion, he said, adding that projected costs would rise as more
information about the scope and nature of soil and groundwater
contamination becomes available.
   Key elements of the weapons complex, including parts of the
Savannah River Plant in South Carolina, the Hanford Reservation in
Washington state, and the Rocky Flats Plant in Colorado, have been
closed down in recent months because of safety and technical
problems.
</TEXT>
