<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 0220EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-Quayle-Conservatives     02-25 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quayle-Conservatives,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Veep Tells Conservatives Bush is One of Them</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle says many of the
changes occurring in the Soviet Union and among its communist
neighbors can be traced to the ``profound impact'' of the defeat of
Soviet forces in Afghanistan.
   In a speech Friday night to the Conservative Political Action
Conference, Quayle said: ``Look at Hungary, where the seeds of
political pluaralism seem to be sprouting.
   ``Look at Poland, where the government is negotiating with
Solidarity.
   ``Look at the ferment of the Baltic states.
   ``And look at the new outspokenness throughout the Soviet Union
itself.''
   He then asked: ``Can it be just a coincidence that all these
remarkable events are taking place at the very same time that the
Soviet Union is reeling from its defeat in Afghanistan? I think
not.''
   The vice president also used his speech to try and assure
conservative activists, often at odds with George Bush, that the new
president would follow in the path of Ronald Reagan.
   ``Those who think that the George Bush, who served at Ronald
Reagan's side for eight years, who worked with him to turn this
country around, will somehow change colors now that he's president _
those people couldn't be more mistaken,'' said Quayle.
   ``The revolution of low taxes, a strong defense, less regulation,
support for freedom fighters and a commitment to moral values that
began in 1981, will continue under the leadership of George Bush
into the 1990s,'' he added.
   But Quayle stopped short of giving the conservatives one pledge
they want _ a commitment the administration will seek military aid
for the Contra rebels fighting to overthrow the leftist government
of Nicaragua.
   He quoted Bush as pledging support for the Contras and said:
``We're going to do what has to be done. ... We're going to have to
see if (Nicaraguan leader) Daniel Ortega means what he says about
free elections.
   ``And if he does not, the people of Nicaragua will continue their
fight for freedom _ and they will deserve our support.''
   But the only specific support he mentioned was for humanitarian
aid.
   ``We're going to insist on the continuance of humanitarian aid to
keep the Contras alive,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890225-0008 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 0221EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-HijackingTrial     02-25 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hijacking Trial,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Chosen, Amal Militiaman to Go on Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury has been picked and sent home for the
weekend pending opening arguments Monday in the trial of suspected
hijacker Fawaz Younis.
   The case tests a 1984 law giving the United States jurisdiction
in incidents involving American hostages abroad.
   U.S. District Judge Aubrey Robinson Jr. asked prospective jurors
whether they had ever been victims of air piracy or had any links
with the Middle East.
   About half the 57 prospective jurors stood up when asked whether
any had heard of the case, in which Younis allegedly led a band of
armed men that seized a Royal Jordanian airliner in Beirut in June
1985. No one was killed in the hijacking.
   The jury, plus four women alternates, went home for the weekend
under strict instructions from Robinson to discuss the case with no
one, including ``your preacher,'' and to avoid media coverage of the
trial.
   In September 1987, Younis was arrested by federal agents who
lured him to a two-masted sailing yacht off the coast of Cyprus in
the Mediterranean Sea with the promise of a drug deal and a party,
according to pretrial evidence and documents.
   Younis was transferred successively to a Navy ammunition ship,
the USS Butte, and a carrier, the USS Saratoga, then flown non-stop
to Andrews Air Force base near Washington.
   The statute under which Younis is being tried was passed in 1984
to give the United States jurisdiction in cases involving American
hostages abroad. Domestic hostage-takers have been convicted under
the statute, but no one besides Younis has been charged with an
overseas hijacking and prosecuted under it.
   The chief prosecutor, Assistant U.S. Attorney Ramsey Johnson,
told the court he planned to call as witnesses six FBI agents, two
Navy doctors and four passengers from the jetliner.
   Defense attorney Francis D. Carter said he would call as
witnesses two federal agents and Helena Cobban, a scholar on the
Middle East. He indicated during a pretrial hearing Wednesday he
will call Younis to the stand.
   Younis, 29, a Shiite Moslem from Lebanon, faces life imprisonment
if convicted.
   Bearded, with brown hair and brown eyes, Younis appeared in the
courtroom wearing a light gray sweater and a tie. Throughout the
proceedings, he smiled and joked with an Arab-language translator
supplied by the court.
   The defense counsel said at a pretrial hearing he would argue
that his client seized control of the airplane under orders from the
Amal militia to which he belonged. The Amal is a Shiite Moslem
faction in Lebanon.
   Evidence against Younis includes a videotape of him on the tarmac
at Beirut airport announcing that the Boeing 727 aircraft would be
blown up. No one was killed in the 39-hour ordeal, which ended when
the airplane was destroyed after being evacuated.
   During the trial, expected to last at least two weeks, federal
officials will be seeking to limit disclosure of details of the
elaborate clandestine operation in which Younis was captured.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
