<FIRST>r a PM-Burglar-Suit     02-25 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burglar-Suit,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Denies Award to Wounded Burglar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors deliberated 19 minutes before rejecting a
confessed burglar's claim for damages against a man who shot him
during his getaway.
   ``We felt we shouldn't reward a burglar,'' jury foreman Vernon P.
Reeves said after the decision was announced in Dade County Court.
   The lawsuit was brought by 19-year-old Fordiran Gonzalez against
Jack B. Lentz, who lived next door to the scene of an August 1987
burglary in Miami. Lentz fired three warning shots, one of which hit
the fleeing Gonzalez in the back.
   The bullet tore through Gonzalez's intestines and went out his
side. The resulting medical bills totaled $8,622.
   Gonzalez admitted taking part in the burglary, and pleaded no
contest to charges in juvenile court. He was ordered to serve 200
hours of community service.
   The youth hung his head in silence when the lawsuit verdict was
read Thursday.
   ``I wish they'd at least paid the bill,'' he said.
   But Judge Philip Bloom said he thought the jurors reached the
right conclusion.
   ``This is a case of chutzpah,'' he said. ``This case highlights
our mixed-up world, in which the admitted criminal seems to have
more rights than an innocent victim. ... This jury verdict affirms
that a burglar is not entitled to safe passage during and after the
commission of that crime.''
   Lentz was originally charged with aggravated battery and culpable
negligence after the shooting. While the charges were later dropped,
he said 17 months of criminal and civil court battles have raised
second thoughts about pulling the trigger.
   If confronted again by burglars, Lentz said, ``I'd have to think
twice about what I'd do. I don't know if I'd get involved.''
</TEXT>
