<FIRST>r i PM-DiscountRate     02-25 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Discount Rate,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Maintains Disagreement With Fed Is One of Economic ``Interpretation''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said today that he and Federal
Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan may disagree about the
``interpretation'' of economic indicators but both men agree on the
need to reduce the federal budget deficit.
   ``We've got a little difference of interpretation at this point
as to how you read the indicators on inflation, and that's the only
difference we've got,'' Bush said in response to questions at an
early morning news conference before leaving Tokyo.
   ``We share the common objectives of needing to get the deficit
down,'' Bush said. ``And I still maintain we are not far apart.''
   Questions about differing views of the economy between Bush and
Greenspan arose anew Friday after the Fed dramatically escalated its
fight against inflation by raising its key bank lending rate to the
highest level in three years. The Fed acted to dampen upward
pressure on prices.
   The move was seen as a repudiation of recent Bush administration
claims that price increases haven't been serious enough to warrant
higher interest rates. Private analysts said the move was long
overdue and should have been stronger.
   The central bank raised the discount rate, the fee it charges for
short-term loans to member banks, from 6.5 percent to 7 percent. The
action was approved on a 6-1 vote with board member Martha Seger
dissenting.
</TEXT>
