<FIRST>r a PM-Names     02-25 0921</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0957</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Newman is 64, looks about 44 and says his
secret is doing what most men dream of when they're about 14.
   ``To be behind the wheel of a car doing over 100 mph is one of
the most exhilarating things I know,'' the actor said in the spring
1989 issue of Men's Health. ``Racing is a way of being a happy child
again.''
   Newman races sports cars about six months a year. When he isn't
doing that or acting, he's running Newman's Own Inc., a $40
million-a-year food business.
   What does he say to those who argue that a 64-year-old actor
driving race cars is unbalanced?
   ``You have to keep things off balance or it's all over,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A longer version of this item moved on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florence Griffith-Joyner is quitting while she's
ahead.
   The 29-year-old track and field star, known for her
record-breaking sprint times and her eye-opening running outfits,
was expected to announce her retirement from racing this weekend.
   She reportedly is retiring to devote time to more lucrative
pursuits off the track. Griffith-Joyner already has signed several
commercial endorsements worth more than $1 million and has received
numerous other offers that could be worth millions more.
   ``Flo-Jo,'' as newspapers tagged her, is probably best known for
her performance at the 1988 Olympic Games in Seoul, South Korea,
where she won three gold medals and one silver medal and shattered
the world record for the 200-meter dash.
   With her long, lacquered fingernails, flowing black hair and
``athletic negligee,'' Griffith-Joyner cut a dramatic figure on and
off the track.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Louise Mandrell has purchased a
``walking piano'' like the one actor Tom Hanks played in the movie
``Big,'' and plans to play it at her concerts.
   Jeannie Ghent, a spokeswoman for the country music performer,
said Friday that Miss Mandrell bought the 14-foot instrument a month
ago at a New York City toy store for $15,000.
   The instrument is a flat, long series of adjoining keys that sit
on the ground. They are played by stepping on them.
   Miss Mandrell plans to use the piano in her act, performing songs
such as ``The William Tell Overture'' and ``Down Yonder.'' She will
place a mirror behind her so the audience will be able to watch the
foot work.
   Miss Mandrell is one of three performing sisters. Barbara
Mandrell is a country music singer and Irlene appears on the
syndicated TV show ``Hee Haw.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MERCED, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steven Stayner is steeling himself for the
inevitable return of the reporters when a television miniseries airs
about his seven years as a childhood kidnapping victim.
   ``I just want to get it over with,'' Stayner said recently. ``As
soon as the movie comes out, the reporters will come back. It will
never go away.''
   Stayner, now 23, was snatched from a street in this central
California farming community on Dec. 4, 1972, when he was 7.
   More than seven years later, his case suddenly became one of the
most publicized kidnappings ever when he and another missing boy,
5-year-old Timothy White, walked into a police station in Ukiah, 150
miles north of Merced.
   A drifter, Kenneth Parnell, was later convicted of kidnapping and
spent five years in prison.
   Stayner's story, a two-part miniseries titled ``I Know My First
Name is Steven,'' is scheduled to run on NBC in May.
   The film is being made with Stayner's cooperation, and he has
agreed to join a publicity tour for Lorimar Productions, which is
making the film.
   ``I don't mind talking about the movie,'' said Stayner. Referring
to his kidnapping, he said, ``It was a terrible experience, but
let's not get overdramatic about it.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PUERTO AYACUCHO, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's Prince Charles
marched into a steaming Amazon rain forest to demonstrate that an
international approach is needed to solve environmental problems.
   ``Rain forests in this part of the world are in essence the lungs
of the world and need to be protected,'' the prince said, adding
that all countries need to learn from primitive societies how to
live with nature without destroying it.
   The prince, on a three-day trip to Venezuela, flew from Caracas
to Puerto Ayacucho, a small town on the Orinoco River, and then
drove off to a rain forest Friday that is home to a tiny community
of Piaroa indians.
   There, the prince sampled a variety of exotic tropical fruits and
marched along a narrow trail through the forest, keeping an
entourage of reporters and camera crews scrambling. He was joined by
deposed King Constantine of Greece.
   The heir to the British throne also declared that solving the
world debt crisis may entail great sacrifice by developed countries.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Cyndi James Gossett, who portrays
Lexie Brooks on the daytime television series ``Days of Our Lives,''
won or shared three awards in the ninth annual Music City Song
Festival.
   Ms. Gossett won awards as a vocalist and songwriter, including
two for the song, ``Lonely Heart'' and one for ``I Never Knew
Love.'' Two of the awards were shared with Paul Wright III.
   ``I'm thrilled,'' she said. ``It will serve as an inspiration for
me to ... pursue a recording career.''
   More than 15,200 entries were received in the annual contest,
which is for professional and amateur singers, songwriters, poets
and lyricists. Music industry professionals chose the winners, which
were announced Friday.
</TEXT>
