<DOCNO> AP890225-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 0238EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Bush-Mideast     02-25 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Mideast,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Says Positive Elements Exist For Solution Of Mideast Conflict</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Saturday that recent
developments in the Middle East present an opportunity for resolving
the 40-year Arab-Israeli conflict, but he cautioned against hasty
U.S. mediation moves.
   Bush said his discussions here with three Mideastern leaders _
Jordan's King Hussein and presidents Hosni Mubarak of Egypt and
Chaim Herzog of Israel _ focused on how best to take advantage of
the changes in the region.
   ``We discussed what new opportunities may exist ... to take
advantage of the positive elements in the current situation,'' Bush
said at a news conference before leaving for China.
   ``I made clear the continuing readiness of the United States to
facilitate this effort in a manner that's consistent with the
security of Israel and the security of our Arab friends in the
region as well,'' Bush said.
   The positive developments Bush listed include the acceptance by
Yasser Arafat, head of the Palestine Liberation Organization, of
Israel's right to exist and his renunciation of terrorism. Arafat's
concessions led the United States to launch a dialogue last December
with the previously banned organization.
   The 14-month Palestinian uprising in the Israeli-occupied
territories has led to ``a recognition on the part of Israel ...
that something needs to be done,'' Bush added.
   ``And I think there's a readiness on the part of other Arab
states to get serious about negotiation and discussions,'' he said.
   Egypt's return to the fold of the Arab world could also serve as
an important catalyst for peace moves, Bush said.
   ``All these are ingredients that I think offer opportunity,'' he
said.
   But he cautioned that ``before we just go rushing out to do
something for the sake of doing something, we take a step that is
prudent.''
   After all, he said, ``I've been in this job for one month, and
this problem has been there for year, after year, after year.''
</TEXT>
