<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     02-25 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Says Kids Face Cancer Risk from Chemicals on Fruit, Vegetables</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private environmental group says preschool
children are consuming cancer-causing chemicals in fruits and
vegetables at levels many times greater than the government
considers safe.
   The findings by the Natural Resources Defense Council were
immediately challenged by the Environmental Protection Agency, which
said in a statement Friday that health risks to children are taken
into account when setting allowable chemical residue levels.
   The Natural Resources Defense Council, a group specializing in
environmental and health matters that has criticized government
policy in numerous areas, is scheduled to announce its findings at a
news conference Monday. An executive summary of the report was
obtained Friday by The Associated Press.
   Janet Hathaway, one of the authors, declined to comment on the
two-year study except to say, ``Our work definitively shows there is
a greatly increased risk to children from chemicals in their diets.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Governors Appointing More Women to State Cabinets</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A women's political group is calling for the
federal government to follow the example of state governors who have
appointed record numbers of women to their cabinets.
   The National Women's Political Caucus said Friday that the number
of women in state cabinets has more than doubled in eight years.
   The group said its survey of the 50 states found 150 women in top
appointed posts, with gains for women coming in all regions and
among governors of both parties.
   It said women now hold 21 percent of all state cabinet jobs
nationwide, adding, ``Clearly this is an area in which the federal
government can learn a great deal from the states.'' Labor Secretary
Elizabeth Dole is the only woman heading one of the Bush
administration's 14 Cabinet departments.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>FAA Proposes $801,000 Fine Against Northwest For Violations</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration says
Northwest Airlines should pay a $801,000 fine for violations
including the use of Boeing jumbo jets on 8,198 flights without a
required engine bolt inspection.
   The airline was also charged with making unauthorized repairs on
two 747s and failure to comply with a dozen other FAA rules and
directives, the FAA said Friday.
   The airline has 15 days to respond to the civil penalty. The
proposed fine amounts to a settlement offer from the FAA which will
take effect if the airline does not object. The FAA said it first
outlined the alleged violations in a Feb. 17 letter to Northwest
President John F. Horn
   William Slattery, Northwest executive vice president for
operations, described the problems as primarily ``instances of
inadequate record keeping and differences in interpretation.''
</TEXT>
