<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 0300EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ThinBlueLine     02-25 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thin Blue Line,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Board Denies Parole To Man Called Innocent In `Thin Blue Line'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man whose conviction for the slaying of a
policeman was questioned in the movie ``The Thin Blue Line'' has
been refused a parole request despite a state judge's strong backing.
   Citing the nature of the crime and use of a weapon in it, the
state Board of Pardons and Paroles voted 2-1 on Friday to deny
parole for Randall Dale Adams.
   Friday's decision means Adams, who was convicted for the 1976
slaying of Dallas policeman Robert Wood, will remain imprisoned even
though his initial accuser _ David Ray Harris _ has recanted and
virtually confessed to the crime.
   Adams' attorney, Randy Schaffer of Houston, criticized the parole
board's decision, saying he was tired of ``having to apologize to
him (Adams) and his mother for the lack of justice in Texas.''
   He said the board routinely paroles convicted killers who have
served fractions of their sentences but is ``absolutely unable to
respond to the case of an innocent man.''
   ``If you put all of that together, what they mean is because
David Harris killed Robert Wood with a gun, then Randall Adams is
denied parole,'' Schaffer said. ``I think their action today
demonstrates why they're the most disrespected parole board in the
country.''
   The parole board scheduled Adams' next review for December 1990.
   Prison officials said Adams could not accept outside calls nor
could he return phone messages.
   The board decided to conduct a special review of the case after
state District Judge Larry Baraka of Dallas recommended to the Texas
Court of Criminal Appeals that Adams receive a new trial or be set
free.
   In December, Baraka recommended a new trial for the 40-year-old
Adams, saying his first trial was unfair because of inadequate
defense attorneys. Baraka, who conducted a three-day hearing on the
matter, also questioned the credibility of witnesses who testified
against Adams.
   The Court of Criminal Appeals may take as long as two years to
act on Baraka's recommendation.
   Baraka also had written to the parole board, urging members to
grant Adams parole.
   The Adams case was the subject of the Errol Morris documentary,
``The Thin Blue Line,'' which strongly suggested that Adams was
innocent of the slaying.
   The documentary accused authorities of railroading Adams and
questioned the credibility of the witnesses against him. Morris was
at work on a film in Detroit Friday and could not be reached for
comment.
   Harris, who was 16 at the time of the Wood murder, said in the
1977 trial he was a passenger in the car when Adams killed Wood, who
had pulled them over.
   But Harris said at the hearing conducted by Baraka that Adams did
not commit the slaying. Harris _ now on death row for the 1985
murder of a Beaumont, Texas, man _ provided so many details about
the crime that Baraka declared his testimony a virtual confession.
</TEXT>
