<FIRST>r a PM-FamilyShooting     02-25 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Family Shooting,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Youth Charged as Juvenile in Shooting of Parents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASPEN HILL, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 12-year-old boy was charged as a
juvenile with murder and attempted murder after police said he
fatally shot his mother and wounded his father with a hunting rifle.
   Matthew Nupp apparently argued with his mother about problems he
had at school earlier Friday before he used the .22-caliber rifle to
shoot the woman once in the head and twice in the side, police
spokesman Sgt. Harry Geehreng said.
   The seventh-grader then chased his father, who arrived home early
from work, out the back door of their suburban Washington, D.C.,
home, firing repeatedly and striking him three times, said Geehreng.
The father, James T. Nupp, 45, went back into the kitchen to
telephone police before he collapsed outside the home, said police.
   The youth holed up inside the house for an hour before
surrendering to heavily-armed police, Geehreng said. His 7-year-old
brother and a 3-year-old child staying at the house at the time of
the shootings were unharmed.
   Geehreng said Evelyn E. Nupp, 45, was dead at the scene. James
Nupp, was listed in fair condition at Suburban Hospital, a hospital
spokeswoman said.
   The boy was held at a juvenile detention facility Friday night,
police said.
   Geehreng said the boy had apparently gotten into trouble Friday
at Parkland Junior High School in Rockville, Md., and was arguing
with his mother when he began firing the bolt-action rifle, one of
three guns the family kept.
   According to Geehreng, James Nupp told police he believed the
rifle, a second hunting rifle and a shotgun he owned had been locked
in the attic.
   Neighbors describe the 12-year-old as a quiet boy who rode his
bicycle in the neighborhood and joined his family on camping trips.
The Nupps were ``a very close-knit family,'' said neighbor Jean
Bowen.
</TEXT>
