<FIRST>r i PM-Bush-JapanMemories 1stLd-Writethru a04328 02-25 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Japan Memories, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0432,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Says Funeral Brought Back Memories of Wartime Comrades</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts lead to show Bush had once had doubts about attending
a Hirohito, sted saying he would have refused to go.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said that 45 years ago, he would not
have believed it possible that he would attend the funeral of
Emperor Hirohito, but said he came to Japan to show he harbors no
bitterness about World War II.
   ``I can't say that in the quiet of the ceremony that my mind
didn't go back to the wonder of it all,'' Bush told a news
conference. ``I vividly remember the personal friends that were in
our squadron that are no longer alive ... but my mind didn't dwell
on that at all.''
   Bush, the youngest pilot in the Navy when he was commissioned,
was shot down by Japanese gunners on Sept. 2, 1944, during a bombing
attack on Chichi Jima. His two crew members were killed and he was
rescued by a passing American submarine.
   ``What I really thought was .. isn't it miraculous what has
happened since the war,'' Bush said.
   Gen. Douglas MacArthur's decision not to prosecute Hirohito for
war crimes ``proved to be correct in terms of Japan's move towards
democracy,'' Bush said.
   There had been criticism of Bush for attending the funeral of
Hirohito, the last of the World War II leaders to die.
   ``I was certain from the day that I committed to come here that
this was correct for the United States. And perhaps, having been in
combat in World War II, maybe the decision was more correct, maybe
it was more profound to be here,'' he said.
   ``We're talking about a friend, we're talking about an ally,'' he
said.
   Bush conceded that if someone had told him 45 years ago, when
there was such ``hard feeling'' about the Japanese leader, that he
would be attending Hirohito's funeral, ``I would have said no way.
But here we are...''
   ``There's a very good lesson for civilized countries in all
this,'' Bush said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
