<DOCNO> AP890225-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 0335EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     02-25 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATTLE CREEK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steve Garrett didn't have a name for
the new parakeet until the bird alerted his sleeping owners to a
fire downstairs. Now, ``Smokey'' fills the bill.
   ``That bird put three smoke detectors to shame,'' Garrett, 30,
said after the fire early Thursday.
   The fire apparently started in an electrical box in the basement,
fire officials said. The parakeet screeched loudly enough from its
first-floor cage to awaken Garrett, who was sleeping upstairs.
   ``I sat up in bed and smelled the smoke,'' said Garrett, 30. ``I
went to see where the fire was. The smoke was so thick that you
couldn't see your hand in front of your face.''
   Garrett awakened his wife Vickie, 18, and they escaped with their
three children and the parakeet. One of the three smoke detectors in
the house began sounding, but not until after firefighters arrived.
   ``He went out as the kids went out and I threw him down (in his
cage) on the porch and kept going with the kids,'' Garrett said,
adding that the bird survived the cold.
   ``We named him Smokey,'' Garrett said. ``He gets anything he
wants. We'll buy him a bigger cage. Maybe we will buy him a
firefighter's suit.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Debbie Hoobler made it to the hospital
just in time to give birth to a girl, but the closest she got to the
delivery room was an elevator.
   ``We just knew it (the baby) was coming quick,'' Mrs. Hoobler
said after giving birth Friday in the elevator at Greenville
Regional Hospital in this northwestern Pennsylvania town. ``I really
didn't have much warning.''
   Mrs. Hoobler had been having contractions for 90 minutes. When
she and her husband, David, reached the hospital after a 15-minute
drive from their home in Stoneboro, they decided to bypass the
hospital's admitting and emergency rooms and go directly to the
second-floor delivery room.
   However, the elevator went down instead of up _ to the basement.
   The baby was born on the way down.
   ``We just got to the hospital, and I said I had to lay down, and
that's where we were, in the elevator,'' said Mrs. Hoobler, who has
five boys ranging in age from 2 to 9.
   The only other person in the elevator was a hospital employee who
is not on the medical staff.
   Hoobler delivered the baby, an 8-pound, 10-ounce girl.
   ``My husband was really good. It didn't bother him at all,'' Mrs.
Hoobler said. ``He had seen all our other babies born. He just went
into action and just did what he had to do.''
</TEXT>
