<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 0345EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Acropolis     02-25 0132</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Acropolis,0135</SECOND>
<HEAD>Piece Of Parthenon Sculpture Found On Acropolis Hill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archeologists say the torso of a centaur
found on the steep hillside of the ancient Acropolis is part of the
curved frieze block that adorned the Parthenon temple.
   The 2-foot-high headless torso was discovered last week by a crew
cleaning the hill, archeologist Constantinos Tsakos said Friday.
   Archeologists classified the sculpture of the mythical half-man,
half-horse as part of the battle of centaurs frieze adorning the
south side of the 5th century B.C. temple.
   Major parts of the frieze are displayed at the British Museum in
London, acquired in 1816 from British statesman Thomas Bruce, earl
of Elgin.
   The Parthenon, being restored in a 10-year project that began in
1985, was decorated with superb sculptures by Pheidias.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
