<HEAD>BULLETIN</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting a0445 to CORRECT dateline</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Arrives in China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush arrived in China Saturday for two
days of talks with government leaders and a nostalgic return to the
city where he served as chief U.S. envoy to Beijing in the mid-1970s.
   Air Force One, bearing the president, his wife Barbara, Secretary
of State James A. Baker III and the presidential party landed at
Beijing International Airport shortly after 4:30 p.m. local time,
3:30 a.m. EST in the United States.
   In advance of his departure from Tokyo, Bush said was excited
about returning to the country that has changed dramatically in the
last several years, and said he hoped to strengthen Sino-American
relations.
