<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 0354EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CocaineArrests     02-25 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cocaine Arrests,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Men Arrested In Money Laundering Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four men were arrested in ``Operation Polar
Cap,'' the continuing federal investigation of a $1 billion cocaine
money-laundering network, authorities said.
   The four San Jose men arrested Friday allegedly helped make cash
deposits of less than $10,000 to banks to evade banking law
requiring that transactions of $10,000 or more be reported to the
Internal Revenue Service, the U.S. attorney's office said.
   Johnny Elias Chawi, 34; Emil Youssel Chawi, 45; Sadir Mouaflack
ajmeh, 32, and Leon Elovits, 38, pleaded innocent in U.S. District
Court to charges they engaged in illegal currency transactions.
   The arrests followed investigations at two liquor stores in
Sunnyvale, a computer store in San Francisco and one in Fremont,
authorities said.
   Thirty-seven people have been charged with taking in at least $1
billion through merchants in Los Angeles, Texas, Florida and New
York, then sending the laundered cash to Colombian drug lords.
   ``Enormous amounts of money generated by the sale of narcotics
were allegedly run through a variety of apparently legitimate
businesses to make it appear to be from legal business activities,''
Matthew B. Pavone, coordinator of the Organized Crime Drug
Enforcement Task Force, said Friday.
   ``These funds were deposited into various banks across the
country and then wire-transferred to countries with bank secrecy
laws and deposited into numbered accounts belonging to various drug
cartel operations,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
