<DOCNO> AP890225-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 0422EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Stockbroker     02-25 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stockbroker,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stockbroker Ordered Held Without Bail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge ordered a stockbroker held without
bail until his trial on charges he bilked clients out of more than
$2 million, saying the former Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. employee
might flee the country.
   ``I do not believe ... that the court has a reasonable assurance
that you will appear'' to face trial if allowed out on bail, U.S.
Magistrate Joyce L. Alexander told Walter F. Curran on Friday.
   ``Notwithstanding family, notwithstanding friends, you might
leave; you have already done it once, and you might do it again,''
Alexander said.
   She noted that when the 46-year-old Boston man was caught at the
Canadian border in Massena, N.Y., on Feb. 17, he had two passports,
an international driver's license, a plane ticket to Germany,
jewelry and the combination to a safe that has not been located.
   Curran persuaded clients to invest money in his personal account
rather than through Dean Witter, promising them 20 percent interest,
then converted the money to his own use, Assistant U.S. Attorney
Peter Mullin said.
   Mullin said the broker also wrote six checks, each for $125,000
to $500,000, on overdrawn bank accounts.
   The prosecutor said the investment and bank frauds involved ``a
total dollar loss of between $2 million and $5 million.''
   Defense attorney Thomas Troy said he would appeal Alexander's
decision.
   Curran is being held at the Middlesex County Jail. If convicted,
he could be sentenced to up to 10 years in jail and a $500,000 fine.
   Mullin said he could not predict when the case would come to
trial, but said it could take months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890225-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 0513EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a CaliforniaPublicUtilityCommissionRestricts976PhoneService
    02-25 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>California Public Utility Commission Restricts 976 Phone Service</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Phone companies must use different prefixes
for calling services with sexually explicit material, supply them
only by subscription and allow businesses to block those calls, a
state agency ruled.
   Friday's action by the California Public Utilities Commission was
hailed as a major ruling by attorney Robert Gnaizda of Public
Advocates, who represented 12 groups that sought changes to protect
consumers and prevent children from ``running up bills of thousands
of dollars'' with the calls.
   The tentative decision, scheduled to come up for a final vote on
March 22, expands a 1987 ruling that allowed residential customers
to block the calls, which typically carry 976 prefixes.
   Businesses and schools have sought the option because many of
their phones are easily accessible and often go unmonitored.
   Recorded and live messages intended only for adults would be
limited to a separate telephone prefix.
   In addition to restricting the services to subscription only, the
commission limited costs to no more than $5 for the first minute and
$1 for each additional minute, with a $20 maximum cost per call.
   Gnaizda said the change in per-minute charges was the most
innovative aspect of the commission's ruling.
   The largest monthly bill for 976 service known to Gnaizda was
$6,000.
   ``Many of them (bills) were in the $5,000 to $6,000 range. So
that's not surprising at all,'' he said.
   But Gnaizda was skeptical about the plan to have phone companies
use three different prefixes to differentiate between services with
sexually explicit material that would be harmful to children, and
provide such messages only by subscription.
   ``They'll never be able to define it,'' he said.
   The commission also said Pacific Bell must contact customers as
soon as the calls reach $150 or more in a billing period, or
temporarily block those services until the customer has been
notified and given the chance to stop it.
   It also said the seller of the phone service must provide an
introductory message warning callers of the call's price and giving
them a chance to hang up without charge.
   ``While this (revised settlement) does not constitute a perfect
900 service, in our judgment it will produce a service with
substantial benefit for California,'' the commission said in a
statement.
   ``Our goal is to disconnect dial-a-porn,'' said Pacific Bell
spokesman Jim Herold. ``But until we have legal authority to do
that, we've designed our new 900 service to solve the problems some
consumers have had with 976.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890225-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 0515EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-976Service     02-25 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-976 Service,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Public Utility Commission Restricts 976 Phone Service</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0456 to RESTORE slugline.</HEAD>
