<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 0532EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     02-25 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strong Snowstorm Blitzes New England Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A powerful snowstorm that dumped as much as 2 feet of snow on the
Middle Atlantic States buffeted the New England coast with winds up
to 52 mph and heavy snow today. Record low temperatures prompted
freeze warnings in Florida.
   Winds gusting to 52 mph in Chatham, Mass., produced blowing and
drifting snow that made it seem like a blizzard, and 6 inches of
snow fell in six hours overnight.
   In Falmouth, Mass., winds gusted to 46 mph and 7 inches of snow
fell. Five inches fell in Portsmouth, R.I. In six hours overnight, 1
inch fell in Boston and Escanaba, Mich.
   Up to 10 inches of snow was expected in southern Maine.
   The storm hit Virginia on Friday with up to 12 inches of snow and
winds gusting to 60 mph that caused hundreds of traffic accidents,
delayed flights, closed schools and businesses and knocked out power
for about 50,000 people, authorities said.
   In New Jersey, 24 inches of snow fell Friday in northern Cape May
County, 18 to 19 inches in Atlantic City and 12 inches in Pomona.
   In Florida early today, temperatures had already dropped into the
mid- to upper 30s as far south as the central part of the state, the
third day of low temperatures. West Palm Beach snapped the 1940
record for the date of 40 degrees with a temperature of 39.
   A hard freeze warning was issued for the northern peninsula, and
a freeze warning was in effect in the central peninsula, where many
citrus and vegetable farms are.
   ``The timing couldn't be worse,'' said grower Cheryl Meeks of
Plant City. ``Strawberries are at their prime. The fields and plants
are loaded; they're just hanging there.''
   Temperatures were also low in much of the rest of the South, with
readings in the 20s and 30s from Mississippi to the Tennessee Valley
and the southern Atlantic Coast.
   Today's forecast called for snow ending over southeast New
England and continuing over much of Maine, upper Michigan and much
of Montana; and scattered rain showers along the northern Pacific
Coast.
   High temperatures were predicted in the teens and 20s from New
England to the lower Great Lakes and eastern sections of the upper
Great Lakes; the 30s and 40s from the middle Atlantic Coast and the
Carolinas to the Tennessee Valley, the Ohio Valley, western parts of
the upper Great Lakes, the upper Mississippi Valley, the northern
Plains, the northern Rockies and the Washington state coast; the 70s
and 80s from southern and western Texas to the southern Rockies and
southern California; and in the 50s and 60s in the rest of the
nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 7
degrees below zero at Massena, N.Y., to 66 degrees at Yuma, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 26 fair; Boston 18 snow; Buffalo 7 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 27 fair; Cincinnati 21 fair; Cleveland 10 fair;
Detroit 21 cloudy; Miami 40 fair; New York 21 windy; Philadelphia 17
partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 8 fair; Portland, Maine 15 snow;
Washington 24 wind.
   _Central: Bismarck 25 fair; Chicago 22 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 44
partly cloudy; Denver 37 partly cloudy; Des Moines 24 fair;
Indianapolis 22 partly cloudy; Kansas City 31 fair; Minneapolis-St.
Paul 31 cloudy; Nashville 22 fair; New Orleans 34 fair; St. Louis 29
fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 43 fair; Anchorage 26 freezing rain; Las Vegas
62 partly cloudy; Los Angeles 58 fair; Phoenix 63 fair; Salt Lake
City 38 cloudy; San Diego 62 partly cloudy; San Francisco 50 partly
cloudy; Seattle 40 rain.
   _Canada: Montreal -1 fair; Toronto 5 fair.
</TEXT>
