<DOCNO> AP890225-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 0554EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MentalPatients     02-25 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mental Patients,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York City To Transfer Mental Patients to Shelters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York City is hoping a program to transfer
some mental patients to shelters for the homeless will help relieve
the severe overcrowding in psychiatric wards, The New York Times
reported today.
   ``We are going to try it on a small scale,'' said First Deputy
Mayor Stanley Brezenoff. ``If it doesn't work, we won't continue
it.''
   The new policy was adopted over the objections of two city
commissioners, the Times said.
   In a memo written by city Human Resources Administrator William
Grinker and Sara L. Kellermann, the commissioner of the city's
Department of Mental Health, the two argued that the plan was
ill-advised.
   ``A policy reversal to discharge ... patients to municipal
shelters at this juncture would discredit the expanded city effort
to treat its most vulnerable population,'' they wrote.
   But Brezenoff said the plan is an attempt at ``pragmatic
humaneness.''
   Shelters receiving the patients would be staffed with
psychiatrists, nurses and social workers to try to help the patients
find a place to live.
   Dr. Luis Marcos, vice president for mental hygiene at the city's
Health and Hospitals Corp., said work has started to provide 46 beds
at two shelters in Manhattan and Brooklyn with mental health
services.
   ``Ideally a shelter is not the optimal residence _ it is a last
resort,'' Marcos said. ``But it is better to discharge appropriate
patients to the shelters than have them inappropriately occupy a
hospital bed that can be used by patients waiting in the emergency
room.''
   Critics of the new plan, however, said all it does is shift
patients from one city agency to another without solving any
problems.
   Many experts say the city's homeless problems stem from a state
decision decades ago to empty beds in state psychiatric hospitals
without any alternatives for those needing assistance.
   The new city plan, some experts said, would repeat the mistakes
of the state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
