<FIRST>u i PM-Philippines-Anniversary 2ndLd-Writethru   02-25 0759</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Anniversary, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0453,0779</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aquino Returns Home For 3rd Anniversary, Shots Disrupt Marcos Rally</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with details on Aquino, Sin quotes.
Picks up graf 4 pvs, `Witnesses said ...' Epifanio delos Santos, graf 3,
is correct. Edits to trim and conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer_</UNK>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shots were fired in the air today as
supporters of former President Ferdinand Marcos scuffled with police
on the third anniversary of the ``people power'' uprising that
propelled Corazon Aquino to the presidency.
   Mrs. Aquino, who returned today from the funeral of Emperor
Hirohito, said international leaders _ among them President Bush _
``they told me that they admire us Filipinos for that non-violent
revolution.''
   She made her comments during festivities along Epifanio delos
Santos Avenue, where hundreds of thousands of civilians massed three
years ago to protect soldiers who had mutinied against Marcos.
   But some prominent Filipinos who helped install her in power
boycotted the festivities to show disappointment with Mrs. Aquino's
leadership. Police estimated today's crowd at 30,000, smaller than
the last two anniversaries.
   In his anniversary address, Manila's Roman Catholic archbishop,
Cardinal Jaime L. Sin, praised the spirit of the uprising but warned
that corruption and political bickering had returned ``to the dismay
of us all.''
   Witnesses said the trouble started when about 3,000 loyalists
rallied near a television station demanding Marcos be allowed to
return from exile in Hawaii. Marcos, in declining health, has lived
in Honolulu since the uprising ended his 20-year rule on Feb. 25,
1986.
   Witnesses said three men bolted from the car and grabbed at least
one Marcos supporter and forced him into their vehicle. When
protesters rushed the car, the intruders fired in the air and sped
away, the witnesses said.
   Later, police Pfc. Albert Gatos said he and two fellow officers
were transporting a robbery suspect to headquarters when the
loyalists attacked their car. Gatos said the ``abducted'' loyalist
had been arrested.
   Today's anniversary celebrations began with the ringing of church
bells across this island nation and included masses, fireworks and
street dancing along Epifanio avenue. Smaller celebrations were
planned in most provincial cities.
   While Mrs. Aquino was in Tokyo for Friday's funeral, the
160,000-member armed forces were on full alert because of coup
rumors sweeping the capital.
   Brig. Gen. Alexander Aguirre said about 2,000 troops would
provide security during the festivities, which will also include a
Roman Catholic Mass, street dancing, fireworks and dedication of a
giant statue of the Virgin Mary.
   Meanwhile, the military said a soldier and two civilians were
arrested outside the capital in a van packed with 1,650 pounds of
explosives. A senior officer said the three are believed linked to
right-wing extremists.
   Lt. Col. Manuel Oxales, deputy chief of the National Capital
Region Defense Command, said the soldier, a second man and a woman
were arrested late Friday in Taytay, a few miles from the
celebration site.
   ``The implication is quite big,'' Oxales said. Asked if the
explosives were meant for a new coup attempt, he said: ``We're
trying to find out.''
   The military also said an officer in a province about 200 miles
southeast of Manila was placed under restrictions for purported
links to renegade Lt. Col. Gregorio Honasan, leader of a 1987
attempt to topple Mrs. Aquino.
   Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile, the former defense minister, said he
would boycott today's festivities.
   ``I will not join the celebrations because I think there is no
cause for celebration,'' Enrile said. ``They really wanted change
for the country, but ... nothing is clear and our future is still
dim.''
   Enrile in his former post led a mutiny against Marcos on Feb. 22,
1986, that triggered the ``people power'' uprising.
   But Enrile later turned against Mrs. Aquino. She fired him as
defense minister on Nov. 23, 1986, after a failed coup by his
followers.
   Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos, another key figure in the 1986
revolt, said today the government needs more time to achieve all its
goals.
   ``We should not be discouraged,'' Ramos told reporters. ``We
should not listen that our government is on the brink of collapse
and that the Filipinos cannot do it.''
   Liberals and leftist activists say Mrs. Aquino tolerates military
abuses of civil rights in the government's 20-year war against
communist guerrillas and has not pressed land reform and other
social programs.
   On Friday, about 10,000 leftists took to the streets in Manila to
express their dissatisfaction with Mrs. Aquino, shouting
anti-government slogans and burning a 10-foot papier mache effigy of
the president.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
