<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 0627EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AbandonedMarine     02-25 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abandoned Marine,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawson Convicted On One Charge In Marine's Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Sentencing scheduled for 10 a.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The only officer charged in connection
with the death of a Marine corporal abandoned in the Mojave Desert
was found guilty of dereliction of duty but innocent of a more
serious charge.
   An eight-officer military jury deliberated more than two hours
before returning a verdict about midnight Friday. It found that 1st
Lt. Allen Lawson had acted improperly by failing to post guides in
pairs during a desert training exercise in August.
   However, Lawson was found innocent of willfully disobeying an
order to provide a roster of men placed in the desert. Lance Cpl.
Jason Rother, 19, died when he was left alone in the Mojave and not
reported missing for two days.
   At sentencing today, Lawson, 25, of Flint, Mich., faced the
possibility of discharge from the Marines and a prison term.
   Lawson also was found guilty of conduct unbecoming an officer for
appearing drunk in downtown Jacksonville in December. That charge
was unconnected with Rother's death.
   In a statement given to reporters before the court-martial
verdict was announced, Lawson said Rother's death was part of the
cost of military preparedness.
   ``It is testimony to the fidelity, hard work and devotion of the
... Marines that Lance Cpl. Rother was the only casualty,'' Lawson
wrote. ``War is dangerous, and training for war is dangerous.''
   But, he added: ``Yes, I am sorry that Lance Cpl. Rother was left
out in the desert, unaccounted for, to fend for himself for 40
hours. I am deeply sorry that he met his demise in the desert.''
   Rother of Minneapolis was posted as a road guide during night
maneuvers at the Marine base in Twentynine Palms, Calif. When the
maneuvers ended, Rother was overlooked by a truck convoy and left in
the desert.
   He was not reported missing for two days, and a search turned up
only some of his equipment and an arrow made of stones at his post.
His remains were discovered Dec. 4.
   Several officers in Rother's battalion were reassigned after a
Marine investigation of the incident, and two sergeants who were
Rother's immediate superiors were convicted by courts-martial and
reduced in rank.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
