<DOCNO> AP890225-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 0638EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-India-Carbide     02-25 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Carbide,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Many Bhopal Claimants May Have Filed False Claims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BHARAT DESAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BHOPAL, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many of the 590,000 people who sought
compensation after the Bhopal gas disaster filed false injury
claims, and about half the claimants may never get any money, relief
officials said today.
   The government is eager to settle claims after Union Carbide
Corp. on Friday finished putting up $470 million ordered by the
Indian Supreme Court to fully settle injury claims. The court
ordered the payment on Feb. 14 to settle claims arising from the
leak, the world's worst industrial disaster.
   ``We have sent repeated reminders to the claimants to get
themselves medically examined or produce documents proving that they
were affected by the toxic gas,'' said a senior official of the
government's Gas Relief and Rehabilitation Department.
   ``But under half of the total claimants have so far come forward
to get themselves certified as gas victims,'' the official said on
condition of anonymity.
   The government was asked Friday to submit a breakdown of how the
funds would be allotted within a week.
   More than 3,400 people were killed by the leak of methyl
isocyanate gas from a Union Carbide pesticide plant on Dec. 3, 1984,
in this central Indian city.
   Victims are still dying at the rate of more than one daily,
medical records indicate.
   The government says 20,000 people are seriously injured by
exposure to the gas. About 590,000 people have filed damage claims,
alleging certain injuries.
   The government set up the Gas Relief and Rehabilitation
Department to handle documentation of claims. About 100 doctors have
been helping bureaucrats identify victims.
   About 250,000 claims have been certified so far, officials said.
   They said they would like to provide money to genuine victims as
soon as possible. Since repeated reminders have failed to produce
medical evidence in so many cases, they said they suspect many
claims are false.
   ``The sooner we can identify the genuine victims, the sooner we
can give them compensation,'' one official said on condition of
anonymity.
   The Indian government initially filed suit on behalf of more than
a half million victims for damages of $3.3 billion.
   Union Carbide is a U.S. multinational company based in Danbury,
Conn.
</TEXT>
