<FIRST>r a PM-ChicagoMayoral     02-25 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chicago Mayoral,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>GOP's Write-In Renegade Puts Party in Spotlight at Last</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some surprise developments enlivened the race for
mayor in its last full week, as a prominent Republican mounted a
write-in campaign and Democrat Richard M. Daley stirred up a racial
issue.
   Both events could spell trouble for Daley in his effort to claim
the office that was once all but owned by his father, the late Mayor
Richard J. Daley.
   Republican Edward Vrdolyak, a former power in the Democratic
Party, on Wednesday gave his blessing to a write-in effort in his
behalf in next Tuesday's primary.
   Ordinarily, a Republican write-in campaign in this Democratic
city would be of little consequence. But some observers believe
Vrdolyak could cut into the lead polls have given Daley in the
Democratic primary.
   The reasoning is that Vrdolyak has a following among some white
ethnic voters who would have been expected to cast their votes for
Daley, rather than Mayor Eugene Sawyer, who is black.
   Meanwhile, Daley, the Cook County state's attorney, was
criticized Friday for remarks he made at a rally before a
predominantly white audience on the Southwest Side.
   John McDermott, chairman of the Committee on Decent, Unbiased
Campaign Tactics, charged that Daley told the crowd: ``You want a
white mayor to sit down with everybody.''
   Daley angrily denied he made a racial comment and some people who
listened to tape recordings said it appeared he merely stumbled over
a word that made it sound like he said ``white mayor.''
   Recent polls have continued to give Daley a lead, but a narrowing
one.
   Whoever wins the Democratic primary will run in the April 4
general election against the winner of the GOP primary as well as
the third-party candidacy of Alderman Timothy Evans, who like Sawyer
is black.
   Vrdolyak is running against GOP-endorsed Herbert Sohn.
   In a radio show taping, Vrdolyak said he hopes to win 10,000
votes, enough to guarantee him the nomination in this Democratic
stronghold. That is half what he got from his own ward in a failed
1987 mayoral bid.
   His big challenge Tuesday will be to get people to properly write
in votes with punch-card voting machines, said Paul Green, a
professor at Governors State University in suburban University Park.
   ``It's physically very difficult to have legal write-ins on a
punch-card system,'' said Green, who follows city politics.
</TEXT>
