<FIRST>r a PM-ProstituteMurders 2ndLd-Writethru a0438 02-25 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prostitute Murders, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0438,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deputy Arrested In Slayings of Three Prostitutes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 5th graf to UPDATE with prosecutor saying
Ross is one of numerous suspects, pickup 6th graf pvs, `The district ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A veteran sheriff's deputy is being held for
investigation into the murders of three prostitutes after he was
arrested while allegedly sharing cocaine with another prostitute.
   Deputy Rickey Ross, 40, was picked up early Thursday by police
officers, and a loaded gun found in the trunk of the county-leased,
unmarked car Ross was driving was linked through ballistics tests to
three 1988 murders, police Chief Daryl Gates and Los Angeles County
Sheriff Sherman Block told a press conference Friday.
   The south-central area of the city, where Ross was arrested, has
been the scene of numerous prostitute slayings since the late 1970s,
including some once attributed to a ``Southside Slayer'' but later
to several suspects.
   Gates would not comment on any possible connection between
unsolved killings and the three murders linked to Ross, who has been
with the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department for 18 years.
   ``There are some differences with other homicides in the
south-central portion of Los Angeles, so this could be three and
only three and we're not speculating that there will be any more
than this,'' Gates said.
   Ross is one of a number of suspects under investigation in a
series of prostitute slayings, Deputy District Attorney Sterling E.
Norris said.
   The district attorney's office is reviewing the evidence on Ross
and a decision on charges will be made Monday, said spokesman Andy
Reynolds.
   Block said Ross, who is married and has two children, ages 20 and
5, had been assigned to a narcotics unit at Los Angeles
International Airport.
   ``He has a very fine record,'' Block said. ``He has been a very
effective investigator in the narcotics bureau.''
   The officers originally arrested Ross for investigation of
driving under the influence of an intoxicating substance. The name
of the woman in the car with Ross was withheld, but Gates said she
told investigators they had been smoking cocaine. Gates said
officers determined she was a prostitute.
   As ballistics testing of the gun found in the trunk was
performed, Ross and investigators went to his home in Rialto, about
55 miles east of downtown Los Angeles. About 5 p.m. Thursday, tests
linked the gun to the three killings and he was arrested for
investigation of murder.
   A search warrant was obtained and the home was searched but Gates
would not reveal any information about what was recovered there.
</TEXT>
