<FIRST>r i PM-Korea-Protests     02-25 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Protests,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Koreans Stage Anti-Bush, Anti-Government Protests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demonstrators today shouted anti-U.S
and anti-government slogans and threw firebombs at police during
protests in several South Korean cities.
   Riot police broke up the rallies, often forming a wall with their
shields. In some cities, police used tear gas and engaged in running
clashes with protesters.
   Police officials said 25,000 riot police were on top alert in
metropolitan Seoul to block protests against the visit Monday of
President Bush. Bush and his wife, Barbara, arrived today in Beijing
for a weekend visit following a stopover in Tokyo for Emperor
Hirohito's funeral.
   The turnout for today's protests was small, with no more than a
few thousand people taking part nationwide. The protesters shouted
slogans, including ``Bush Go Home!'' and ``Down With Roh Tae-woo!''
   The nation's largest dissident alliance issued a statement
demanding Bush cancel his visit, which it said was designed to
bolster the government of South Korean President Roh Tae-woo. Roh
marks his first anniversary in office today.
   ``The United States is scheming, through Bush's visit, to
perpetuate the division of the Korean peninsula, stabilize the
military dictatorship and heighten tensions,'' said the United
National Democratic Movement of Korea.
   About 500 radical students gathered at South Gate, one of Seoul's
ancient city gates, and shouted slogans, but police dispersed them
and arrested some. Police used tear gas to break up 200 students
holding a rally near the Seoul railway station.
   About 100 dissidents held a rally inside a downtown Seoul church
to demand Roh's ouster.
   In the provincial city of Kwangju, riot police blocked a planned
rally, and students and farmers armed with rocks and firebombs
fought running battles with police, who fired tear gas, the news
agency Yonhap said.
   Dissidents also have called for protest rallies Monday to oppose
the Bush visit.
</TEXT>
