<FIRST>r a PM-Navajos-MacDonald     02-25 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Navajos-MacDonald,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navajo Supreme Court Blocks Lower Court on MacDonald Issue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDOW ROCK, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Navajo Tribal Chairman Peter MacDonald
plans ``business as usual,'' despite a court order removing him from
office for the second time this month, a spokeswoman says.
   The Navajo Supreme Court on Friday overturned an order by Keyenta
tribal District Judge Harry Brown that reinstated MacDonald as
chairman pending a full hearing of the case.
   The Supreme Court also ordered Brown, who is MacDonald's
brother-in-law, to show cause Tuesday why he shouldn't be removed
from the case.
   After being served with the Supreme Court order, Brown canceled
the hearing he had scheduled to consider the validity of a Feb. 17
Tribal Council vote that placed MacDonald and Vice Chairman Johnny
R. Thompson on administrative leave.
   MacDonald was accused of corruption earlier this month in
Congressional hearings.
   In the wake of the Supreme Court's order, tribal delegate
Marshall Plummer said it was his understanding that he was once more
in charge of the 88-member council. He was elected council chairman
pro tempore in the disputed vote last week.
   ``We are in control now. This shows that the Tribal Council has
got the authority,'' Plummer said.
   However, MacDonald spokeswoman Tazbah McCullah said MacDonald
still believes he is in charge despite the council action and the
Supreme Court's decision.
   MacDonald planned a busy weekend of executive functions,
including speeches in several communities. ``It's business as
usual,'' she said.
