<FIRST>u i PM-BushRdp 7thLd-Writethru a0484 02-25 1111</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush Rdp, 7th Ld-Writethru, a0484,1,080</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Urges Chinese to Join in Working for Peace, Stability</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS new graf after pvs 4th graf bgng, ``We owe, with Chinese
president's banquet toast; INSERTS new graf after pvs 18th graf bgng, Bush
disclosed, with report of Baker's meeting with Chinese foreign minister.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush flew to China today, clasped hands
with ordinary people in Beijing's main square and urged Chinese
leaders to join the United States in planting trees of world peace
so future generations ``can sit together in the shade.''
   The president and his wife, Barbara, were jubilant on their
return to the country where Bush served as America's diplomatic
representative in the mid-1970s. ``It's great to be back,'' he
declared.
   At a welcoming banquet in the Great Hall of the People, Bush
toasted his host, President Yang Shangkun, and recalled a Chinese
proverb that says ``one generation plants a tree, the next sits in
its shade.''
   `We owe it to mankind to work together for peace and
international stability,'' Bush said. ``Let us continue, then, to
work together, to plant trees together, so that the next generation,
ours and yours, can sit together in the shade.''
   In response, Yang praised Bush for making ``great contributions
to developing Chinese-U.S. relations.'' He said that ``steady
development of these relations will be of enormous significance.''
   Thousands of people crowded along the wide, flag-draped boulevard
in front of Tiananmen Square, where Bush hopped from his limousine
to shake some hands. It was his fifth visit to China since he spent
two years as the chief U.S. envoy to Beijing before formal
Sino-American relations were restored.
   ``Welcome back,'' someone called out to Bush in English. The
president replied in tentative Chinese, ``Xie xie (thank you).''
   From the airport, where he arrived in late afternoon from Tokyo,
Bush was driven to the Diaoyutai State Guest House for a formal
welcome over tea with Premier Li Peng.
   The president gave Li a pair of Texas boots and the premier gave
Bush and his wife, Barbara, a couple of bicycles. When he lived here
previously, Bush was known for his habit of biking around the
capital.
   En route, Mrs. Bush told reporters she was excited to be
returning to China.
   Seeing the country for the first time was like seeing ``a black
and white movie,'' she said. ``Last time we were there _ three or
four years ago _ it was really an emerged nation. I love China. I
had very, very happy years there.''
   At Tiananmen Square, where U.S. and Chinese flags flew side by
side, Chinese people halted their bicycles for a curious glimpse at
their American guest. A few of them applauded.
   The Bushes visit here blends sentiment and statecraft. Before
leaving Tokyo, the president declared that his talks with 20 foreign
leaders in the Japanese capital had yielded ``a shared sense of
satisfaction'' with the course of East-West relations, and laid a
good foundation for advancing the security interests of the United
States and its allies.
   Bush arrived at Beijing's old airport, now used only by
high-ranking Chinese officials and visiting dignitaries. Bush,
wearing an overcoat in 40-degree weather, waved once as he descended
the ramp. He was followed by his wife, who wore a purple coat.
   In keeping with Chinese custom, there was no arrival ceremony or
statements. Bush was greeted by Vice Premier Wu Xuequian and Vice
Foreign Minister Zhu Qizhen, and two children gave the president and
his wife bouquets of flowers.
   ``I know I will marvel at the changes'' in China since he served
as head of the U.S. Liaison Office in 1974-75, Bush told reporters
earlier. He said ``we obviously have differences'' but that his
visit would strength an already-solid relationship.
   ``I'm excited about it. There's an openness in China that I never
would have predicted 15 years ago,'' he said.
   His Beijing talks were to focus on Sino-American ties, with
glancing attention to an overflow cup of topics that could spark
debate _ including reunifying Taiwan with the mainland, human rights
in Tibet and trade issues.
   Bush disclosed that he will meet in Beijing with Cambodian
opposition leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk, whom the United States
favors as leader of an interim government following a pullout of
Vietnamese occupation forces. The president said the United States
was seeking to prevent the Chinese-backed Khmer Rouge from returning
to power in Cambodia.
   At a separate meeting, Secretary of State James A. Baker III and
Chinese Foreign Minister Qian Qichend agreed that Vietnam should
withdraw from Cambodia as soon as possible and expressed support for
Sihanouk's peace efforts, the Chinese news agency Xinhua reported.
   Bush's itinerary included meetings with the four leaders who call
the shots for China's government and Communist Party. He departs for
Seoul en route home to Washington on Monday.
   His agenda Sunday included a Protestant worship service, a
private meeting with Premier Li Peng and a reciprocal banquet for
Chinese leaders featuring Texas barbecued ribs and Lone Star beer.
   He also is scheduled to meet with senior leader Deng Xiaoping,
attend a reception with U.S. Embassy personnel and confer with
Communist Party General Secretary Zhao Ziyang.
   Deng and Yang represent the old guard of pre-liberation
revolutionaries, while Zhao and Li are younger and more in tune with
goals of guiding China's 1 billion people toward economic prosperity.
   Before leaving Tokyo, Bush held a news conference in the
residence of the U.S. ambassador, where he vowed to continue the
fight for Tower's confirmation.
   Bush said he was firmly behind Tower, whose nomination was
spurned 11-9 by the Senate Armed Services Committee Thursday, saying
he had no ``fallback'' planned except to lobby strongly with
``whoever has an open mind on the subject.''
   In fact, White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater told
reporters accompanying Bush to China on Air Force One that Tower
would undertake a public relations offensive next week, making a
speech to the National Press Club and appearing on television
interview programs. He said that Bush will meet with a dozen
senators Tuesday to seek support for Tower.
   Before leaving Tokyo, Bush met briefly at the Imperial Palace
with Japan's new emperor, Akihito, before sitting down separately
with Presidents Jose Sarney of Brazil and Ibrahim Babangida of
Nigeria, bringing to 20 the number of foreign leaders he has met
with in two days.
   Summing up his fast-paced diplomacy in Tokyo, Bush said:
   ``Throughout all of our discussions ... I found a shared sense of
satisfaction ... that East-West relations are now clearly proceeding
on the basis of an agenda favorable to the United States, its
allies, its friends.''
</TEXT>
