<FIRST>r i PM-Nicaragua-Soviets     02-25 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua-Soviets,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet To Reconsider Arms Shipments To Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Ambassador Valery Nikolaenko
said Moscow will reasses its arms shipments to the leftist
Sandinista government because it wants to help end regional
conflicts.
   Central America's troubles ``cannot be solved militarily, only
through peaceful means, through negotiation,'' Nikolaenko told a
news conference Friday. He also praised the region's latest peace
plan. The agreement was signed by the five Central American
presidents in El Salvador on Feb. 14.
   During the summit, President Daniel Ortega agreed to hold
elections in February 1990, 10 months earlier than expected, to
guarantee the integrity of those elections and to ensure that
opposition parties have equal access to radio and television air
time during the campaigns.
   Ortega and his counterparts in Guatemala, El Salvador, Honduras
and Costa Rica also agreed to draft within 90 days a detailed
program to effect ``the demobilization, repatriation or voluntary
relocation in third countries'' of an estimated 20,000 Nicaraguan
rebels and their families in neighboring Honduras.
   The U.S.-backed rebels, known as the Contras, have been fighting
Nicaragua's government from bases in Honduras since 1981. In
February 1988, Congress stopped military aid to the Contras. Top
officials of the Bush administration have indicated they may support
the peace plan.
   The Kremlin's ambassador to Nicaragua distributed a statement
praising the Central American summit.
   ``The results of the meeting ... are evaluated positively by the
Soviet Union and are considered as an aspiration by these countries
to win a new push in the negotiation process directed at winning a
definitive political arrangement of the critical situation in the
area,'' the statement said.
   It said the Soviet Union ``is willing to actively contribute to
the advance of reparation of the situation in Central America, the
affirmation of peace, being good neighbors and cooperation between
the countries in the region.''
   Nikolaenko said Moscow plans ``a more thorough examination'' of
future weapons shipments to Nicaragua.
   He would not reveal how much military aid the Soviet Union
provides Nicaragua, but he said last year it exceeded $300 million.
   ``This help each year varies, although this year there are no
major changes,'' he said, adding the Soviet Union will continue
sending aid to Nicaragua ``without imposing any political ideology.''
   ``We are happy with any economic, political and social model the
Nicaraguan revolution decides to take,'' Nikolaenko said, adding
that the Sandinista revolution ``has gained great prestige.''
   When asked whether the Soviet Union will provide financial
assistance to Nicaragua if the Sandinista government is defeated,
the ambassador replied: ``We respect the sovereign decisions of
individual countries.''
</TEXT>
