<HEAD>Queen Appeals To Veteran To End Hirohito Hunger Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Britain-Hirohito</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Queen Elizabeth II appealed to a World War II
veteran today to end his hunger strike protest over Prince Philip's
attendance at the funeral of Emperor Hirohito of Japan.
   ``The queen is aware of his situation and now that the funeral is
over we hope that he will end his hunger strike,'' Buckingham Palace
said in a statement.
   There was no immediate reaction to the latest appeal from
70-year-old Andrew Burgess, who has been eating nothing and drinking
only black tea for the last nine days.
   During an appearance Friday night on Central Television's Weekend
Live program, Burgess rejected an earlier palace appeal to give up
the hunger strike.
   But Burgess said he might consider ending his fast if Prince
Philip announced he was stepping down as patron of the Burma Star
Association, a veterans group. Burgess is treasurer of the
association's Swansea branch.
   ``Prince Philip has sentenced me to death. Obviously the royals
don't give a damn about me or the brave men who laid down their
lives for king and country,'' he said.
   Burgess said British and Commonwealth prisoners of war were
``degraded in every possible way'' by their Japanese captors and the
presence of the queen's husband at the funeral was an insult to the
memory of thousands of brave men.
   He asked the queen to forgive him for starving himself to death.
   On Friday, while Hirohito's funeral was taking place, thousands
of British veterans attended services to remember the comrades lost
fighting the Japanese and vent the anger they still share.
   There were more than 25 services at war memorials and in churches
from Wales to Blackpool. Some veterans also celebrated the funeral
in pubs, and some refused to speak to a Japanese reporter at one
service.
