<FIRST>r i PM-Obit-Menen     02-25 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Menen,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aubrey Menen, Author and Critic, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aubrey Menen, a novelist, essay writer
and critic, has died of throat cancer, according to news reports. He
was 76.
   Menen was working on a book based on traditional family life in
his father's native state, Kerala, when he died Feb. 13.
   Menen was born in London in 1912 and lived mostly there after
taking British citizenship. However, he had been living in the
southern city of Trivandrum, capital of Kerala, since 1985.
   He wrote more than 25 books, including novels, short stories and
autobiographies. His first book, ``Prevalence of Witches,'' was
published in 1947. Other works included ``The Stumbling Stone,''
``The Backward Bride,'' ``The Fig Tree'' and ``Space Within the
Heart,'' an autobiography.
   Most of Menen's books were published in Britain, the United
States and India. He also wrote articles for Time and Life magazines
and contributed to literary journals.
   Two books by Menen, ``Ivory Horses'' and ``Kitchen in the
Gondola,'' will be published soon, his companion Graham Hall, told
The Statesman, a Calcutta newspaper.
   Menen, a bachelor, was cremated in Trivandrum.
</TEXT>
