<DOCNO> AP890225-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 0945EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Psychiatry     02-25 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Psychiatry,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Americans To Examine Soviet Psychiatric Patients For Alleged Abuses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union, which says it has stopped
committing sane political dissidents to psychiatric hospitals, will
get a chance to prove that claim when a group of Amerian
psychiatrists visits Sunday.
   About 20 psychiatrists, accompanied by a State Department
official, arrive Sunday for a three week visit and will meet with
Soviets they suspect are being held in psychiatric institutions for
political reasons.
   A Soviet official said on Friday that the Americans will see that
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of perestroika, or
restructuring of Soviet society, has improved psychiatric treatment.
   ``They will be given the opportunity to familiarize themselves
with the system of psychiatric help in the U.S.S.R. and the positive
changes taking place in this area,'' said Yuri Reshetov of the
Foreign Ministry.
   The Americans will visit mental institutions, examine patients
and meet with Soviet psychiatrists, said Reshetov, head of the
ministry's international humanitarian cooperation and human rights
directorate.
   He said the trip was organized by the U.S. State and Health and
Human Services departments and the Soviet Foreign and Health
ministries.
   Neither Reshetov nor American officials would provide an
itinerary.
   Allowing U.S. officials into once-secret psychiatric institutions
is another example of Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or greater
openness.
   Abuse of psychiatry in the Soviet Union has been a contentious
issue between the superpowers for decades.
   Gorbachev, as part of a wide-ranging effort to improve the Soviet
Union's human rights record and restore credibility to his country's
health system, has taken steps to end abuse of psychiatry.
   In January 1988, the Soviet press reported some pyschiatric
hospitals were being transferred from the domain of the police to
the Health Ministry and that a new law made it a crime to commit a
sane person to a mental institution.
   Last month, the head of the Soviet psychiatrists' society, Georgy
Morozov, said: ``There are no patients in mental hospitals in the
U.S.S.R. who are there for political reasons.''
   Moscow activist Alexander Podrabinik and others have rejected
that claim. They say 20 to 30 healthy people remain in psychiatric
hospitals and in many cases are forcibly injected with mind-altering
drugs.
   The State Department last month credited the Soviets with
``significant progress'' in the treatment of political prisoners. It
said the Kremlin had freed all those held under laws limiting
expressions of political and religious beliefs, but that it still
had questions about 30 prisoners whom Soviet authorities consider to
be criminals.
   While many Western psychiatrists acknowledge the Kremlin has
freed most people committed to asylums for political reasons, they
have demanded an admission of past abuses.
   One Soviet publication came close in November.
   Mikhail I. Buyanov, a psychiatrist and neurologist, wrote in the
education newspaper Uchitelskaya Gazeta that Soviet psychiatry was
systematically used in the 1970s to suppress dissidents by declaring
them mentally ill and committing them to asylums. But he said
officials still haven't fully admitted mistakes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
