<FIRST>u i PM-SAfrica-Stompie 1stLd-Writethru a0481 02-25 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Stompie, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0481,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slain Teen-Age Activist Recives Hero's Burial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with burial, ANC statement. Pickup
6th graf pvs, ``Seipei's death...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUMAHOLE, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stompie Seipei, the 14-year-old
activist allegedly killed by Winnie Mandela's bodyguards, was
eulogized today as a hero at a funeral marked by calls for black
militance and unity.
   Chanting youths ran ahead of the hearse to the cemetery where
Seipei's small wooden casket was buried.
   Mrs. Mandela, wife of jailed African National Congress leader
Nelson Mandela, was not mentioned by name in a funeral service at a
Roman Catholic church in Tumahole, a black township 60 miles
southwest of Johannesburg.
   The 500 mourners at the church sang freedom songs and chanted
their loyalty to the ANC guerrilla movement and Mandela, the
country's best known black leader. The crowd swelled to 1,000 for
Seipei's burial.
   ``We shouldn't point fingers at other people because Stompie was
interested in unity,'' said a local anti-apartheid leader, McLean
Skhosane, at the service. ``Don't let his death divide us.''
   The African National Congress today issued a statement from
Lusaka, Zambia, calling on blacks to avoid ``fratricidal'' attacks
in the townships.
   Seipei's death is at the center of a controversy surrounding Mrs.
Mandela and her group of bodyguards, known as the Mandela United
Football Club.
   Seipei and three young men staying at a Methodist Church
sanctuary in the Soweto township outside Johannesburg allegedly were
abducted to Mrs. Mandela's home in late December and assaulted there
by members of Mandela United.
   Seipei's body was found in a Soweto field Jan. 6, police said.
Two members of Mandela United have been charged with murder, while
the team bus driver also has been arrested but not charged. Mrs.
Mandela has denied any personal involvement in Seipei's death.
   The reasons for Seipei's alleged abduction and beating remain
unclear.
   Mrs. Mandela has said the youths were taken from the Methodist
church because they were being sexually abused by a minister.
   However, Methodist church officials said after conducting an
investigation that there was no truth to Mrs. Mandela's allegations.
No reason has been given for the alleged beating of Seipei, although
there are numerous rivalries among black groups in the townships.
   Seipei is one of four people killed the last two months who had
direct or indirect links to either Mrs. Mandela or Mandela United.
   Seipei became an anti-apartheid activist at age 10, when he and a
friend formed the ``Under Fourteens'' in Tumahole.
   More than 1,000 youths served under Seipei's command in the
well-organized children's army, challenging local police and
pro-government vigilantes during the height of black township unrest
in 1985-86.
   ``The other groups were all talk and no action,'' the 4-foot
activist told a British journalist in 1987. ``We formed an army to
protect the people from harassment.''
   At age 11, he was detained for the first time, becoming the
youngest person held under state-of-emergency regulations.
   He learned chess and tried to keep up with studies that were
interrupted when he left primary school in 1986.
   Colleagues said his political awareness was remarkable, and he
could recite sections of important political documents by heart.
</TEXT>
