<FIRST>u i PM-Mideast-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru a0479 02-25 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mideast-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0479,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze Wants Foreign Warships Out Of Persian Gulf</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Soviet minister calling for withdrawl
of all foreign warships from the gulf. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet foreign minister today called for
the removal of all foreign warships from the Persian Gulf and said
Moscow is ready to withdraw its fleet to help revive stalled
Iran-Iraq peace talks.
   The minister, Eduard Shevardnadze, said he expressed Moscow's
concern about the continued presence of U.S. and other Western
navies in the strategic waterway despite the 6-month-old cease-fire
in Iran-Iraq war.
   He later left for Tehran on the last leg of a 10-day, five-nation
Middle East tour and said he will hold talks with Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini, who rarely meets with foreign dignitaries, on peace
efforts in the gulf region.
   But he did not say whether he would discuss Khomeini's death
sentence on British novelist Salman Rushdie whose prize-winning book
``The Satanic Verses'' is considered by Iran and other Moslem
nations to be offensive to Islam. Clerics in Iran have placed a $5.2
million bounty on the head of Rushdie, who was born a Moslem in
Bombay, India, but who now lives in London.
   Sources in London said on Friday that Britain has asked
Shevardnadze to press Iran to renounce its death threat. A source in
Britain's Foreign Office source said today that Britain has not
received a reply from the Soviets.
   Iran's reaction to Rushdie's novel was criticized by President
Bush and led Common Market countries to recall their senior
diplomats in Tehran in protest.
   After two days of talks with Iraqi leaders, Shevardnadze told a
news conference in Baghdad today: ``Our views were identical that
there is a need for joint eforts by all countries in the gulf to
clear the general atmosphere and maintain security in the area.''
   Speaking in Russian through an interpreter, Shevardnadze said an
international agreement could be reached by all parties using the
gulf with full guarantees from the five permanent members of the
U.N. Security Council: the Soviet Union, the United States, Britain,
China and France.
   Sheverdnadze's call appeared to be directed primarily at the
United States, which has reduced its fleet in the gulf region but
still has 23 warships there. The Soviets have a much smaller naval
force in the waterway. Italy, Belgium and the Netherlands, which
sent naval flotillas into the gulf in July 1987 to support U.S.
moves to protect shipping, have all withdrawn their ships.
   France still has some mine sweepers in the gulf, but Britain
plans to withdraw the last of its mine sweepers in the next week or
two.
   Iran has repeatedly demanded the withdrawal of foreign navies.
   Shevardnadze said: ``I will not rule out that the parties
benefiting from the gulf will conclude an agreement on how to
implement their international obligations within a common order
agreed upon by all.''
   He said he agreed with Iraqi President Saddam Hussein and other
Iraqi leaders on ways of solving the problem of the foreign naval
presence in the waterway. But he did not elaborate.
   U.N.-mediated peace talks between Iran and Iraq have been stalled
since the Aug. 20 cease-fire on a variety of issues, including a
dispute over the Shatt-al-Arab waterway which flows along their
border.
</TEXT>
