<FIRST>u i PM-SatanicVerses 2ndLd-Writethru a0485 02-25 0736</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Satanic Verses, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0485,0751</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Says Other Countries to Pull Envoys From Iran</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with reaction to Howe's statement from
nations he named, Japan refusing to ban book, Malaysia banning it. No pickup.</UNK>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British official today said other countries have
agreed to join the 12 Common Market nations in withdrawing their
ambassadors from Iran to protest Tehran's death threat against
novelist Salman Rushdie.
   Sir Geoffrey Howe, the foreign secretary, said Austria, Finland
``and a number of other countries'' he did not identify had decided
to remove their top envoys from Tehran.
   He spoke in a British Broadcasting Corp. radio interview from
Tokyo, where he attended the funeral of Emperor Hirohito and met
with representatives of other nations to ask support of the
diplomatic moves engineered by Britain.
   Austria's ambassador to Tehran, Herbert Traxl has been
vacationing in Vienna since Monday, said government officials, who
would not say whether he would be withdrawn.
   Finland has called Iran's ambassador to Helsinki to protest the
death threat. There was no immediate comment from government
officials on whether Finland's ambassador would be recalled.
   Howe also mentioned Norway, Sweden and Canada, but they already
have recalled envoys for consulations.
   Rushdie, who was born a Moslem in Bombay, India, is a naturalized
British citizen who now lives in London. He has been hiding under
police protection since Iran's leader, Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini,
called on others last week to kill him, saying his novel ``The
Satanic Verses'' blasphemes Islam. Iranian clerics offered a bounty
of up to $5.2 million for Rushdie's death.
   Official sources said Friday that Britain had asked Soviet
Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze to press Iran to renounce its
death threat when he meets Khomeini during a visit to Iran today. A
Foreign Office source said today that Britain had not received a
reply from the Soviets.
   Rushdie, 41, has said he did not intend to slander Islam, but he
nevertheless issued a public apology for any offense his novel has
caused Moslems, who have protested worldwide against the book.
   Police patrolled Bombay today to prevent further violence there,
and protests against the book were reported in northern England and
in Malaysia.
   Howe said in today's interview that several Moslem countries had
made clear ``they certainly would not go along with the type of
conduct which we complained of in Iran.'' He cited Pakistan as an
example of a Moslem country that ``has been prepared to uphold the
rule of law against violent protest.''
   ``I think that's a measure of the way in which the rest of the
world does not want to associate itself with the wholly
unjustifiable, intemperate incitements to murder that have emerged
from Iran,'' Howe said.
   At least seven people were killed Feb. 12-13 in protests in
Pakistan and in India's northern Jammu-Kashmir state. The book has
been banned in Pakistan, South Africa, Bangladesh, Iran, India and
Egypt.
   Malaysia also banned the novel today.
   In Bombay, India, police today fanned out in large numbers across
the city to prevent further violence after street protests against
the novel left at least nine people dead and 40 injured on Friday.
   Initial news reports said up to 12 died in protests over the
book, but a police commissioner, S.M. Shangari, said eight people
died in the rioting and one man died later in the hospital. Peaceful
protest also were reported Friday in New Delhi, Calcutta and several
other Indian cities.
   The governing Congress Party of Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi of
India today denounced the death threat against Rushdie. Press Trust
of India quoted Party General Secretary K.N. Singh as saying: ``We
always deprecate violence and terrorism of all kinds, individual or
state.''
   In response to the death calls by Khomeini, the 12 nations of the
European Economic Community earlier this week recalled their top
envoys from Iran, and London has shut down its mission in Tehran.
Iran retaliated by pulling its ambassadors out of the Common Market
nations. Besides Britain, the Common Market nations include Belgium,
France, West Germany, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Denmark,
Greece, Ireland, Portugal and Spain.
   Japan's foreign minister, Sousuke Uno, said Friday he opposes any
international leader's advocacy of murder but that his nation has no
plans to withdraw its ambassador from Iran.
   Uno said, however, that the topic probably will come up when he
meets on Sunday with Iranian Vice President Mostafa Mir Salim.
</TEXT>
