<SECOND>AM-BRF--Japan-Fires,0113</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fires Killed More Than 2,000 in 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A record 2,116 people died in fires in Japan in
1988, and most fires were caused by hot plates and cigarettes, fire
officials said Saturday.
   In an annual report, the Fire Defense Agency said the death toll
was up 13.9 percent from the previous year. However, the total
number of fires _ 59,653 _ was the second lowest in a decade, it
said.
   Damage from fires totaled $1.1 billion, the lowest figure since
1979, the agency added.
   Of the fires, 7,146 originated in hot plates, the largest single
cause, while fires caused by cigarettes came second with 6,266.
</TEXT>
