<FIRST>r i AM-HongKong-Protest     02-25 0148</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hong Kong-Protest,0151</SECOND>
<HEAD>Demonstrators Protest Japanese Militarism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100 people demonstrated at a downtown park
Saturday against Japanese militarism during World War II and
denounced the late Japanese Emperor Hirohito as a war criminal.
   The protesters, chanting slogans and carrying banners, also
accused the Japanese government of rewriting school textbooks to
gloss over Japanese wartime atrocities.
   The demonstrators, who claimed they represented students,
academic and labor organizations, said they were concerned that
Japan does not recognize its responsibility for the war.
   After the half-hour rally, the protesters marched to the Japanese
Consulate, where they handed in a petition accusing the Japanese
government of rewriting the history of the war.
   Historians generally regard Hirohito, who died Jan. 7, as just a
figurehead, although the war was waged in his name. Hirohito was
buried Saturday.
   Hong Kong was occupied by the Japanese during the war.
