<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 1118EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Electrician'sArrest     02-25 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Electrician's Arrest,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Electrician Charged With Manslaughter In Fatal Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fatal house fire that authorities say
was caused by an improperly installed baseboard heater has led to
the arrest of the electrician who hooked up the unit.
   Richard Salz, 48, was arrested Friday and charged with
second-degree manslaughter. He was released on $1,000 bond pending a
March 6 court appearance.
   ``I'm not a criminal. It was a faulty heater,'' said Salz, owner
of Salz &amp; Son Electrical &amp; General Contractors. ``These people are
looking for something that is not there.''
   Burton Gorman III, 13, of East Haven died in a fire Dec. 28. The
boy was found dead of smoke inhalation in his second-floor bedroom
in the home he shared with his grandparents, his father and a
brother.
   The fire was caused by a ``meltdown'' in a basement heating unit
that was improperly wired, said Deputy Police Chief William Hubbard.
   Joe Toscano, an inspector with the New Haven state's attorney's
office, said he knew of no other cases in the state in which an
electrician has been held responsible for a fire death.
   More than a dozen electrical code violations, including the
absence of a ground wire, were discovered in the six-foot baseboard
heating unit Salz installed in the Gorman home, Toscano said.
   ``He did not install that unit using sound electrical practices.
If this were just a case of mistakenly doing one thing, I don't
think we would be here today,'' Toscano said.
   Salz said he performed the work in August as an individual, and
not as part of a contract with his company.
   ``All I did was install it under the instructions of the
homeowners. There is no way anyone can hold me responsible here,''
he said.
   To prove second-degree manslaughter, Toscano said, prosecutors
will have to show that as a licensed electrician, Salz should have
known that what he was doing posed a fire hazard but went ahead
anyway.
</TEXT>
