<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 1115EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SouthKorea-US Bjt   02-25 0774</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Korea-US, Bjt,0792</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Visits Seoul Amid Growing Anti-U.S. Mood</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush visits South Korea on
Monday at a time when anti-American sentiment is growing
dramatically, with many Koreans demanding sweeping changes in
relations with their closest ally.
   During a brief visit, Bush is expected to discuss ways to reduce
friction and to review the friendship. U.S. and South Korean
officials say relations are excellent, but they want to ensure
anti-American sentiment does not threaten their ties.
   Anti-Americanism has mushroomed among groups ranging from radical
students to conservative farmers, all accusing the United States of
exploiting South Korea. Complaints range from claims of military
occupation to unfair trade pressure and cultural insensitivity.
   As South Korea has become stronger in recent years, growing
nationalism and resentment of some U.S. policies have aggravated
anti-American sentiment, analysts say. The United States also has
been singled out as a target by anti-government groups trying to
gain support by whipping up nationalist sentiment, they say.
   Koreans resent ``U.S. interference in domestic politics and
economy in a high-handed manner, its support for dictatorship, and
its coercive demands to open Korean markets,'' the Chosun Ilbo
newspaper said in a recent editorial.
   The change has been sudden and dramatic in a nation that saw the
United States as a savior for coming to its aid during the Korean
War. Many Koreans remain friendly toward the United States, analysts
say, but anti-American sentiment is becoming embedded among some
groups, especially younger people.
   Nationalistic pride is particularly strong among those who have
no memories of how U.S. troops helped save the South from a North
Korean invasion in 1950, analysts say.
   ``They (the young) demand enhanced sense of national identity,
expecting their country to play an active role independent from
foreign pressures, not the role which resulted in humiliating
national tragedy,'' The Korea Herald said in a Feb. 19 editorial.
   Many South Koreans, proud of the enormous gains their nation has
made in becoming one of Asia's economic powerhouses, feel the United
States has failed to recognize their strength and growing role in
the world. The United States, many Koreans say, treats South Korea
as an underling, when it should regard Seoul as an equal.
   Radical students seeking the fall of President Roh Tae-woo claim
his government is a military dictatorship controlled by the United
States. Radical leaders demand the removal of the 42,000 U.S. troops
based in South Korea, claiming the United States is blocking
reunification with communist North Korea.
   Students and other dissidents have mounted a wave of violent
anti-U.S. protests since 1988 and attacked U.S. diplomatic offices
and military bases with homemade explosives and firebombs.
   ``It is a fact we cannot ignore that the United States and its
proxy ruling force (the South Korean government) are primarily
responsible for all our country's problems and divisions,'' said a
radical student leader, who declined to be named.
   Such radicals reject the broad democratic reforms introduced by
Roh with strong American support since 1987. But the students have
little public support because of their extremism.
   Some opposition parties reject the radicals' violent tactics but
also criticize the United States for backing the authoritarian
regimes that have dominated South Korea for much of its history.
   ``The fundamental cause of anti-Americanism is American attitudes
in the past,'' Kim Dae-jung, head of the main opposition Party for
Peace and Democracy, said in an interview.
   Opposition leaders want an end to any major U.S. role in internal
affairs, including American command over most of the South Korean
armed forces and the special status exempting U.S. soldiers from
local prosecution in some criminal cases.
   Yet all opposition parties favor close ties with Washington and
agree the United States should be their principal ally. Opinion
polls indicate a majority of South Koreans want U.S. troops to
remain as long as there is a threat from North Korea.
   Anti-American sentiment also has been stirred by U.S. pressure on
Seoul to open South Korean markets to American imports and help
reduce Washington's trade debt with Seoul, which was $8.6 billion in
1988. Farmers opposed to any U.S. imports have staged violent
protests, and some Koreans fear the United States is trying to
cripple South Korea's economy.
   South Korean officials agree the opposition to American imports
is unfair given the open access South Korea has to U.S. markets. But
they argue South Korea is a developing nation and Washington should
consider Korean feelings.
   ``The American authorities seem to take it for granted that
people also think and behave in the same way as Americans do,'' said
political analyst Kim Byong-kui.
</TEXT>
