<FIRST>r i AM-SouthKorea     02-25 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Korea,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radicals Protest Bush Visit; Security Forces on Alert</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Korea-US, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot troops in at least six cities
broke up violent protests Saturday by radicals yelling ``Bush go
home!'' and the government put 120,000 police on alert to prepare
for the president's visit.
   Students hurling firebombs and rocks battled riot police in minor
running clashes in some provincial cities. Thousands of riot police
blocked demonstrations, often forming a human wall with shields to
disperse protesters. Dissident groups had called for nationwide
protests Saturday to demand the fall of President Roh Tae-woo's
government and to protest Bush's visit Monday. But turnout was small
and riot police overwhelmed the few thousand people who took part.
   Authorities said police would remain on top alert because
dissidents have called for more protests Monday. Radicals are
demanding an end to close ties with the United States and removal of
42,000 U.S. troops based in South Korea.
   The nation's largest dissident alliance, the United National
Democratic Movement of Korea, demanded Bush cancel a visit it said
was designed to bolster the Roh government. Bush is to visit Seoul
for about five hours to hold talks with Roh and address the National
Assembly.
   ``The United States is scheming, through Bush's visit, to
perpetuate the division of the Korean peninsula, stabilize the
military dictatorship and heighten tensions,'' the movement said.
   About 50 students broke through a police guard and threw
firebombs and rocks at a district office of the governing Democratic
Justice Party in southern Seoul. They also firebombed another of the
party's offices in the southern city of Yosu, said Yonhap, the
Korean news agency.
   A few hundred radicals braved heavy rain and a massive police
presence to demonstrate in downtown Seoul. Police arrested about 70
protesters.
   ``Kick out the Americans!'' the radical students shouted.
   About 100 dissidents rallied inside a downtown Seoul church.
   Police fired tear gas to break up a rally of 200 students near
Seoul railway station.
   About 500 more protesters shouted slogans at South Gate, one of
Seoul's ancient city gates, but police dispersed them and arrested
some.
   In the provincial city of Kwangju, riot police blocked a planned
rally, and students and farmers armed with rocks and firebombs
fought running battles with police, who fired tear gas, Yonhap said.
Minor clashes also were reported in the central city of Chungju and
Masan in the south.
   In the southern city of Chonju, about 200 students staged an
anti-government rally and attacked two police stations, smashing
several windows and setting fire to telephones and furniture, Yonhap
said. Farmers and students later staged separate street protests.
</TEXT>
