<FIRST>r i AM-Bush-Commotion     02-25 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Commotion,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Like It or Not, Thousands Crowd Streets At Bush Return</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people, some curious, some just
trapped in the throng, were on the streets Saturday as President
Bush was welcomed in Beijing.
   ``Look at all those cars,'' 4-year-old Gao Xiaofeng gushed as the
presidential motorcade cruised down Changan Street, Beijing's main
boulevard.
   ``I remember seeing the new president on his bicycle in Beijing
15 years ago,'' said the boy's father, Gao Feng. ``He certainly is
traveling differently now.''
   At Tiananmen Square, in the heart of Beijing, the president and
Mrs. Bush stepped out of their car and greeted ordinary Chinese
citizens.
   Onlookers applauded them. The Bushes stayed on the square for two
minutes and posed for photos. They then sped to the state guest
house, Diaoyutai, for a welcoming ceremony with Premier Li Peng.
   Amid the commotion, some Chinese acknowledged they didn't know
George Bush.
   ``Bush?'' said a puzzled university student. ``I thought Ronald
Reagan was coming to China.''
   Others couldn't recognize the Stars and Stripes, which was hung
side-by side with China's flag along the huge square.
   ``That must be the flag of Pakistan,'' said an elderly woman.
   But one bystander, Zhang Jun, said he thought Bush was ``a real
gentleman. I hope his visit makes Chinese-American relations even
better.''
   ``So do I,'' added Wang Luo, leaning on his bicycle, ``but he's
making me late for dinner.''
   Indeed, about 20 minutes before the motorcade drove by, police
stopped all traffic on Beijing's main boulevard. Thousands of
bicycling commuters joined curious passers-by as they waited on the
sidewalk for the president to pass.
   ``I'd like to strangle these bureaucrats to death for shutting
the city down for another big potato,'' yelled one man, as he
balanced his son on his handlebars. ``My boy is sick and the cold is
bad for his health.''
   ``Let's move it, let's go,'' others yelled as the throng surged
forward.
   Police did not let people go on their way until 10 minutes after
the motorcade passed.
   Bush, who headed the U.S. Liaison Office in Beijing in 1974 and
1975, is well-liked in China, a country that puts much emphasis on
personal relations. Bush and his wife, Barbara, are famed in Beijing
for their bicycle excursions around the city.
   On bustling Wangfujing Street, there was less interest in their
return.
   ``I don't have much to say about Mr. Bush,'' said one woman as
she juggled several bags of spinach, onions and meat. ``I have to
run home and cook.''
</TEXT>
