<DOCNO> AP890225-0070 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 1148EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-BushPastor 630   02-25 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Bush Pastor, 630</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Secret Service Dismays Chinese Pastor</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The security demands of the U.S. Secret Service
bewildered and dismayed a Beijing church pastor, who was greeting
President Bush and his wife Barbara at a special Sunday morning
church service.
   First the agents wanted to examine several Chinese-language
Bibles and hymnals that the Rev. Kan Xueqing and his fellow
ministers planned to give the Bushes. Then they demanded the church
doors be closed to worshippers more than an hour before the start of
the service.
   The security officials also had initially insisted that church
members not to be told of the service until two days beforehand _
when in a practically telephone-less society, it would be difficult
to get word out.
   The restrictions were modified slightly after Kan expressed
concerns about impingement on local customs.
   Western ministers might have expected such demands. But to the
67-year-old Kan, who most of his career has faced athiest communist
restrictions on worship, the security precautions were
incomprehensible.
   ``It has been very difficult. I was upset,'' Kan said Friday as
White House technicians installed lights and sound equipment in the
86-year-old brick Chongwenmen Protestant Church.
   ``They want to close off all the entrances to the street leading
to our church. The freedom of our believers to come to church to
worship will be restricted,'' he said. After decades of communist
suppression, that is a freedom Chinese Christians don't take
lightly, he said.
   ``I never thought the United States would give us this problem,''
Kan added. ``Maybe atheists would.''
   Kan's church, located in a walled compound down a narrow alley,
is one of six Protestant churches serving the Beijing metropolitan
area. Its single service at 9:30 a.m. each Sunday usually is filled
to capacity with about 1,500 people.
   For the Bushes, the church planned a special, half-hour service
at 8 a.m.
   Kan said he was overjoyed when he learned Bush, a former
parisioner of his, was to come.
   The minister had conducted Sunday services for Beijing's small
foreign community in a former YMCA hall in the early 1970s. Bush and
his wife, Barbara, were regular worshippers during Bush's 1974-75
stint as head of the U.S. Liaison Office before full U.S.-Chinese
diplomatic ties were established.
   ``Some of this is the problem that (Kan) hoped it would be like
the old days when the Bushes rode up on their bicyles,'' said U.S.
Embassy spokesman Sheridan W. Bell. ``But he is president now.''
   During their stay in the 1970s, the Bushes were famous for their
penchant for riding bikes, the favorite Chinese mode of
transportation.
   Kan said he understood the Secret Service's responsibility to
protect Bush. But he added, ``I am a pastor. I am a friend of so
many years. I heard ministers are respected in U.S. society, not
like here, where you say, `I'm a pastor' and people say, `What's
that?'''
   His protests have been heeded. The White House sent him a letter
late this week, he said, assuring him it would respect Chinese
customs.
   The Secret Service backed off on examining the gift books and
agreed to keep the church doors open until half an hour before the
service.
   They also let him announce the service half a day earlier so he
could tell church members who came to a Thursday night prayer
service.
   White House staffers ``are trying to be as sensitive and polite
as they can,'' Bell said.
   Kan said he prayed and decided he should understand the Secret
Service's viewpoint. ``Their thinking and mine are not the same,''
he said. ``They are doing it for Bush.''
   His hope, he said, was that Bush's attendance would stimulate
interest in Christianity in China.
   ``I believe God has arranged a very good opportunity to spread
the Gospel,'' in the officially atheist society, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
