<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 1150EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Bush-Sihanouk     02-25 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Sihanouk,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush to Meet Cambodian Resistance Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to fix keyword line garble; Top prospects uncertain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush was looking Sunday to advance
efforts to promote peace in Cambodia, meeting with Cambodian
resistance leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk during his visit to
Beijing.
   Both the president and the flamboyant prince are staying in
villas at the secluded Diaoyutai guest house, which served as a
retreat for Chinese emperors for 800 years.
   Sihanouk, who has been living at the guest house for more than a
month, has spent the past decade wandering in exile in Beijing,
North Korea and Paris. He has frequently quarreled with his
resistance partners but remains intent on ending Vietnam's 10-year
occupation of his country.
   The United States provides non-lethal assistance to Sihanouk's
faction and a second non-Communist opposition faction headed by Son
Sann.
   The third resistance force is the Khmer Rouge, infamous for its
fanatic rule from 1975 to 1978 that resulted in the deaths of 1
million Cambodians.
   Vietnam says it will not leave Cambodia until it is certain the
Khmer Rouge won't return to power. Bush has said he would press the
Chinese, the main supplier of arms to the Khmer Rouge, to ensure the
group is prevented from resuming its reign of terror.
   The resistance has held two rounds of talks in recent months with
the Vietnamese-installed government of Cambodia regarding the future
course of the country, but little progress was reported.
   Sihanouk, 66, was driven from the Cambodian throne in 1970 in a
coup he claimed was engineered by the Central Intelligence Agency.
   He took a strong anti-American stand and returned to his homeland
in 1975 when the Khmer Rouge gained power. But he was immediately
placed under house arrest and many of his family members were killed.
   He went into exile in 1979 when Vietnam invaded and has since
relied on China, Thailand and the West for support in the resistance
struggle.
   Earlier this month, in an exchange of letters with the new
Secretary of State, James A. Baker III, Sihanouk said: ``We
Cambodian patriots ask the United States to play a more important
and active role in the search for a fair solution to the problem of
Cambodia.''
   Baker wrote, ``without question, your leadership is crucial to
achieving an acceptable Cambodian settlement'' and urged Sihanouk to
remain involved in efforts to reach a settlement in his country.
   Several days later Sihanouk, who had quit his official positions
with the resistance a year earlier following a dispute with the
Khmer Rouge, announced he was resuming his post of president of the
resistance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890225-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 1151EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Aids     02-25 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Aids,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>WHO Says Dirty Syringe Caused AIDS Outbreak in Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A World Health Organization official agrees with
Soviet conclusions that an unsterile syringe infected more than two
dozen children with the AIDS virus, Tass said Saturday.
   David Heimann, chief of the WHO epidemiological department, came
to the Soviet Union to help medical authorities track the source of
the virus discovered in 29 infants and six mothers in Elista, a city
near the Caspian Sea.
   ``Large-scale epidemiological studies helped find the cause of
the massive infection of the children _ an unsterilized syringe used
for injections at a maternity home,'' said Tass, the official Soviet
news agency.
   The virus itself, Tass said, ``was most probably brought by a man
who worked in one of the African countries eight years ago.''
   Not everyone infected with the AIDS virus contracts the deadly
disease.
   The news agency said Heimann ``received full information and did
not find any data contradicting the conclusions of the Soviet
national commission which held a probe into the accident.''
   It was not clear in the Tass report how the virus was transmitted
from the unidentified carrier, but earlier newspaper reports said
nurses at the maternity home had been reusing disposable syringes to
cover up the sale of unused needles to drug addicts.
   The toll of 29 infected infants in Elitsa is two more than
reported in January, and authorities are continuing to test hundreds
of infants who were treated in the hospital.
   Heimann offered the support of the international community,
saying, ``it would be useful to jointly work out methods of treating
the infected children and providing psychological support for their
mothers,'' Tass said.
   After long denying the existence of acquired immune deficiency
syndrome in the Soviet Union, officials acknowledged about three
years ago that Soviets have been infected and began a campaign
against the disease.
   Since 1987, it has been a crime in the Soviet Union to infect
anyone with the AIDS virus, and officials are investigating bringing
charges against medical personnel in the Elitsa case. Since the
presence of AIDS was acknowledged in the Soviet Union, officials
have reported that two people have died of the disease.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that
damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to
infections and cancer.
   It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or
syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products,
and from pregnant women to their offspring.
   The scientific name for the virus is human immunodeficiency
virus, or HIV.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
