<FIRST>r i AM-Vietnam-USDoctors     02-25 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vietnam-US Doctors,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Doctors Operate On 101 Vietnamese Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first U.S. doctors to work in
Communist Vietnam have operated successfully on 101 children, who
suffered mouth deformities, the official Vietnam News Agency said
Saturday.
   It said former Prime Minister Pham Van Dong received the doctors
from ``Operation Smile'' at the presidential palace in the capital,
Hanoi, on Friday and told them he hopes the two countries increase
cooperation in medical and other fields.
   Seven plastic surgeons and two other physicians corrected cleft
lips and palates of children at the Olof Palme Institute for the
Protection of Children's Health, said the report, monitored in
Bangkok.
   ``Operation Smile'' is a Norfolk, Va.-based agency and one of
various private charitable groups that have responded to a U.S.
government call for more humanitarian aid to Hanoi.
   The aid call was partly in response to Hanoi's help in resolving
cases of U.S. soldiers missing in the Vietnam War. The Pentagon says
2,383 Americans are unaccounted for.
   The United States has not established diplomatic relations with
Vietnam since the communists defeated the U.S.-backed South Vietnam
government in April 1975 and reunified the country. However, in the
last two years, more and more private American citizens have visited
Vietnam.
</TEXT>
