<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 1253EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Wrapup-Rushdie     02-25 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wrapup-Rushdie,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rushdie Profile: `One of Nature's Outsiders'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Wrapup-Iran Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: This is one of a package of ``Wrapup'' stories on the controversy
over ``The Satanic Verses.'' Also moved in advance Feb. 23 as b0585.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salman Rushdie, whose novel ``The Satanic Verses''
prompted Iranian religious leaders to demand his death for allegedly
blaspheming Islam, was born a Moslem in Bombay, India, on June 19,
1947.
   Tall and slender, his black hair thinning above a bespectacled,
fine-featured face, he seems to wear a permanently serious
expression.
   His late father was a wealthy businessman who sent him at age 13
to the prestigious Rugby school in England. Rushdie won a
scholarship to Cambridge University, studying history and developing
an interest in the life of Islam's founder, the Prophet Mohammed.
   From Cambridge he joined his parents in Moslem Pakistan, working
in the country's fledgling TV service. He said the political and
religious prejudice he encountered made him return to England.
   He eked out a living writing advertising copy and two TV films.
His first novel, ``Grimus'' in 1975, drew no critical attention.
   His second, ``Midnight's Children'' in 1981, a tale of those born
at the moment of India's independence in 1947, made his name and won
the Booker Prize and the coveted James Tait Black Memorial Prize.
   ``Shame,'' his third novel, in 1983, treated Pakistan's politics
as myth and was not popular, although it won a prize in France. Then
followed a Nicaragua travel book, ``The Jaguar Smile,'' in 1987 and,
last September, ``The Satanic Verses,'' which won the Whitbread
Prize for a new novel.
   Rushdie has a son from his first marriage in 1976 to Clarissa
Luard. In hiding from the death threats, reportedly with an armed
police guard, he is with his second wife, American novelist Marianne
Wiggins.
   Philip Howard, literary editor of The Times of London, described
Rushdie as the ``stormy petrel, wayward genius, of our younger
novelists; very clever, over-the-top and self-indulgent in his
poetic prose, egotistical, prickly and political, very keen on money
for a professed socialist: one of nature's outsiders.''
   Peregrine Worsthorne, editor of London's conservative Sunday
Telegraph, said it was ``ironic that someone who was only recently
inveighing against Mrs. (Prime Minister Margaret) Thatcher for
having created a police state should now be compelled to rely on
that same police state to save his life.''
   The left-wing New Statesman magazine described Rushdie as ``an
ungratefully rich author who not only believes that writers and
politicians are natural rivals, but acts on that uncomfortable
belief, both in his writings and personal life.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890225-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 1257EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Wrapup-Book     02-25 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wrapup-Book,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Bewildering and, They Say, Blasphemous Journey</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Wrapup-Iran Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: This is one of a package of ``Wrapup'' stories on the controversy
over ``The Satanic Verses.'' Also moved in advance Feb. 23 as b0586.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Mahound is a businessman who decides to start a new religion in
the city of Jahilia. Only problem, Jahilia already has 360 gods and
doesn't need another.
   But the head of the ruling council proproses a deal: If Mahound's
Allah (the Islamic god) will accept three of the local gods _ Lat,
Uzza and Manat _ as archangels in his sect, he can have his religion
and also a seat on the council. He takes the deal.
   Mahound appears in a dream sequence in the Salman Rushdie book,
``The Satanic Verses.'' He represents Mohammed, revered by Moslems
as the prophet who set down Allah's revelations in the Koran,
Islam's holy book. And the novel's portrayal of Mahound-Mohammed _
as a womanizer, a moral coward willing to compromise his faith for
general acceptance, a conniving businessman who makes up laws to
suit his own purposes _ has inflamed the Islamic world.
   ``The Satanic Verses'' is a dizzying 547-page journey through
countless plots, sub-plots, satire and philosophical questions.
   Lyrical, scathing, inquisitive and, at times, bewildering, the
novel's subjects include society's preconceptions of good and evil,
the British treatment of illegal aliens, the desire by Indians to
become assimilated in British culture and, most notably, the birth
of the Islamic faith.
   Rushdie, a 41-year-old native of Bombay, India, who now lives in
London, writes in a stream-of-consciousness style that leaves the
reader alternately exhilirated, bewildered and _ depending on one's
religious and political orientation _ outraged.
   The book opens with the bombing of a jumbo jet by terrorists. Two
of the passengers _ Gibreel Farishta, an Indian actor who
specializes in religious roles, and Saladin Chamcha, a radio star _
manage to survive by literally falling from the sky. Once they land,
Gibreel assumes an ``angelic glow'' and Saladin grows horns and
hooves.
   The book's second, fourth, and sixth chapters, ``Mahound,''
``Ayesha'' and ``Return to Jahilia,'' contain the most controversial
elements involving Gibreel's dream sequence.
   During the dream, Mahound has a revelation in Gibreel's presence
telling him to accept the deal. But he soon learns that the
supposedly divine message did not come from Gibreel (the archangel)
but from the Devil, who had been impersonating him.
   Mahound renounces the satanic ``verses.'' He and his followers
settle in the ``friendly oasis'' of Yathrib, just as Mohammed
journeyed from Mecca to Medina. There Mahound dictates to a Persian
scribe named Salman the rules of the new religion as prescribed by
Gibreel. But Salman doubts these ``revelations'' because God sounds
too much like a businessman.
   Convinced that Mahound is making up the rules himself, Salman
decides to test his leader by deliberately changing what is recited
to him:
   ``Here's the point: Mahound did not notice the alterations. So
there I was, actually writing the Book, or rewriting, anyway,
polluting the word of God with my own profane language. But, good
heavens, if my poor words could not be distinguished from the
Revelation by God's own Messenger, then what did that mean? What did
that say about the quality of the divine poetry? Look, I swear, I
was shaken to my soul.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890225-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 1257EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Wrapup-Bookstores     02-25 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wrapup-Bookstores,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chain Bookstores Stiffen Their Spines</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Wrapup-Iran Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: This is one of a package of ``Wrapup'' stories on the controversy
over ``The Satanic Verses.'' Note that Trace, in 4th graf, is correct.
Also moved in advance Feb. 23 as b0589.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's biggest booksellers, stiffening
their spines in the face of terrorist threats, have reversed
themselves and declared they will display and sell ``The Satanic
Verses'' after all.
   With their statements, B. Dalton, Barnes &amp; Noble and Waldenbooks
sought to quell a furious protest over their initial moves to pull
the book from their shelves when Iran threatened death to its author
and handlers.
   But it took a statement from President Bush and pleas from their
own employees for the chains to budge. In the end, their
discomfiture made for an awkward and painful drama in which the
shadow of terrorism fell over an unlikely setting, the local
bookstore.
   ``The decision all along has been one of safety. Whether or not
to stand on the front lines against terrorism was not a decision
Waldenbooks wanted to make on behalf of its 8,500 employees,'' said
spokesman Trace Urdan.
   Critics said more than safety was at stake. After initial
hesitation, writers held rallies and readings to support author
Salman Rushdie and to denounce the bookstore chains for abandoning
the freedom of expression.
   ``Rushdie the individual yields place to Rushdie the symbol of
our freedom to write and to publish what we want,'' said author
Diana Trilling.
   Author Norman Mailer spoke of the precedent: ``In this week of
turmoil, we can now envision a fearful time in the future when
fundamentalist groups in America, stealing their page from this
international episode, will know how to apply the same methods to
American writers and bookstores.''
   One result of the controversy _ probably unintended by Iran,
which said ``The Satanic Verses'' blasphemes against Islam _ has
been heightened demand for the book. Already a best seller on some
regional newspaper lists, it will be No. 2 on The New York Times
list of March 2.
   ``Certainly, the prominent news attention the book has received
has created a great demand for it,'' said a spokesman for Viking
Penguin, the novel's U.S. publisher. ``We are trying to meet that
demand.''
   While the three bookstore chains account for an estimated 25
percent of U.S. book sales, their gyrations meant little practically
because the book's first U.S. printing of 50,000 copies already was
largely sold out. With tens of thousands on order, a second printing
of 15,000 has begun to reach bookstores and a third printing, of
more than 50,000, was begun.
   B. Dalton and its affiliated Barnes &amp; Noble said it decided to
stock the book at the urging of its employees and in light of a
statement by President Bush, who denounced Iran's threats.
Waldenbooks said it decided to allow its managers to display the
book, at their discretion, when many asked to do so.
   Waldenbooks noted that it has received about 60 bomb threats, and
complained in a national newspaper advertisement that its employees
had suffered ``unfair castigation'' for the initial decision to pull
the book.
   ``We do not feel that this is a censorship issue,'' said Urdan,
the Waldenbooks spokesman. ``But obviously there are many who
disagree.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890225-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 1258EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-AfghanHighway     02-25 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghan Highway,0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Road To Pakistan Nearly Deserted</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALONG THE JALALABAD HIGHWAY, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the pot-holed
road winds out of the Afghan capital, a tattered poster, its colors
fading, declares ``Kabul is a city of peace.''
   This 100-mile road leads from the Afghan capital east toward
Jalalabad and then onto Pakistan across the Khyber Pass.
   Gunfire erupts sporatically in the suburbs. As travelers ride
through some of the country's most spectacular mountain scenery,
they watch nervously in fear of a rocket attack by Moslem guerrillas
who have infiltrated the area.
   The Afghan government refuses to say to what extent the
guerrillas have penetrated, but it insists the strategic road is
open.
   Scenes along the route suggest otherwise.
   The road is deserted, except a few women drawing water from
nearby wells and men watching Soviet-made trucks hauling supplies to
what would become the muddy front-line of Kabul's defense if
Jalalabad fell to the guerrillas fighting Afghanistan's communist
government.
   The only other travelers who regularly dare this gauntlet are
Pashtun-speaking tribesmen taking their scrawny camels to meat
markets in Kabul.
   In the distance, Afghanistan's war machines are visible.
   Dozens of Soviet tanks left behind for the Afghan army after the
Kremlin's soldiers withdrew are parked on the snow-covered
mountains, easy guerrilla targets.
   At Tangiye Pol-i-Charki, south of the country's most notorious
prison, nervous Afghan soldiers wait at a checkpoint, their rifles
cocked and tin helmets squashed over their Russian-made fur hats.
   The checkpoint's proximity, about 20 miles south of Kabul, is an
indication of the precarious hold the army has had over the highway
since the first Soviet armored columns started leaving Afghanistan
on May 15.
   ``I'm sorry, you can't go any further without special permission
from the Interior Ministry,'' said one soldier as he opened the car
trunk and glove compartment, searching for weapons. ``There is much
fighting out there.''
   The soldier, who would not give his name, said he and six
comrades had been recruited recently in preparation for a final
showdown between the guerrillas and the Afghan armed forces
following the departure of Soviet troops Feb. 15.
   Watching them closely were two stern-looking members of KHAD, the
Soviet-style secret police assigned the task of maintaining loyalty
among the army.
   The soldier, speaking through a government-sponsored interpreter,
refused to talk about the fighting.
   But he said a convoy carrying fruit, vegetables and firewood from
Pakistan had been delayed because some trucks had run out of fuel.
   Kabul has been plagued by shortages of fuel and heating oil, and
the situation has forced some families to burn tree branches to try
to heat their mud-and-brick homes when the temperature drops to 5
degrees.
   Aside from the convoys, the only other travelers were the camel
trains.
   Tribesmen bring their camels from Pakistan, a journey that takes
at least seven days, to markets in Kabul. But the sparse supply
sells for as much as $10 a pound, too expensive for most Afghans.
   The tribesmen said most of the trip is done at night because of
threats by the guerrillas, called mujahedeen, or Islamic holy
warriors.
   ``The mujahedeen don't want us to bring our camels to Kabul,''
said Ghulam, a camel dealer. ``They say we're helping the government
and they will shoot us if we don't stop.''
   He said the guerrillas have never carried out their threat. Some
diplomats and observers believe some tribesmen have secretly agreed
to carry weapons and ammunition in a deal that allows them to travel
through the guerrilla-dominated countryside.
   Ghulam insisted he and his friends have never carried arms for
the guerrillas. He said they never would.
   ``We don't like them,'' he said. ``And we're not going to stop.
This is our way of life.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
