<FIRST>r w AM-GeriatricJets-Incidents     02-25 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Geriatric Jets-Incidents,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>With Geriatric Jets Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some of the recent incidents involving
airliner aging and metal fatigue prior to damage that killed nine
people Friday when an 18-year-old United Air Lines 747 tore open
over the Pacific. Cause of the incident had not been determined:
   January 20, 1989 _ A Piedmont Airlines 737's dropped an engine
shortly after takeoff from Chicago. None of 3 passengers and crew
was injured and the plane landed safely. The aircraft was only seven
years old, but authorities blamed metal fatigue and a cracked bolt.
   December 26, 1988 _ An late 1960s Eastern Airlines Boeing 727
with 104 passengers and six crew aboard was forced to land at Yeager
Airport in Charleston, W.Va., after a 14-inch hole opened in its
fuselage at 31,000 feet. There were no injuries. The incident led to
fleetwide inspection and discovery of a 3-inch crack in another old
Eastern 727.
   Sept. 21, 1988 _ An American Airlines 727 made a belly landing at
Dallas-Fort Worth after metal fatigue in its landing gear prevented
the pilot from opening the wheel well door. The 88 passengers and
crew evacuated with three people injured. Boeing had recommended
inspections eight days earlier after finding metal fatigue in the
same area in other 727s.
   May 9, 1988 _ A 20-year-old American Airlines 727 was forced to
make an unscheduled landing at Detroit after a 15-inch crack in a
wheel well caused a drop in cabin pressure. None of the 112 aboard
was injured.
   April 28, 1988 _ A flight attendant was killed and 61 persons
injured when a portion of the fuselage on a heavily flown Aloha
Airlines 737 built in the late 1960s peeled off at 24,000 feet
during an Aloha flight from Hilo to Honolulu. Tiny cracks were found
later in nearly half the aging Boeing 737 jetliners inspected in the
months following and the FAA ordered the reriveting of hundreds of
older 737s.
   Dec. 5, 1987 _ An engine fell of a USAir 737 in Philadelphia,
causing no injuries. The FAA ordered inspection of engine-mount
bolts on some 737s.
</TEXT>
