<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 1324EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Wrapup-Chronology 1stLd-Writethrub0587sentFeb23   02-25
0723</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wrapup-Chronology, 1st Ld-Writethru b0587 sent Feb 23,0736</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Wrapup-Iran Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds two grafs to UPDATE with events Friday and Saturday. This
is one of a package of ``Wrapup'' stories on the controversy over ``The
Satanic Verses.'' Also moved in advance Feb. 23 as b0587.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of the controversy over ``The Satanic
Verses.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1988</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 22 _ ``The Satanic Verses,'' a 547-page satirical fantasy
that parodies some elements of Moslem faith, is published by Viking
Penguin Inc. in England. It is the sixth book for Salman Rushdie,
41, a Bombay-born British citizen who has given up his Moslem faith.
The novel wins him the Whitbread Novel Award and critical acclaim.
   Oct. 5 _ Rushdie's native India bans the book as blasphemous,
barring its import and sale, and fears militant Moslems may use it
to incite riots. Rushdie protests the ban, which later spreads to
Pakistan, Bangladesh, Egypt, Iran, Saudi Arabia and other Moslem
countries.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>1989</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 14 _ About 1,500 Moslems in Bradford, England, burn a copy
of the book and protest its content. W.H. Smith and Sons Ltd. pulls
the book from its London stores despite the protests of Rushdie and
other writers.
   Feb. 4 _ 3,000 Moslems march against the book in Birmingham,
England.
   Feb. 12 _ Six people die and 83 are injured as police fire
semi-automatic weapons at 3,000 fundamentalists who storm the U.S.
Information Center in Islamabad, Pakistan, demanding the book be
banned in the United States. Sixty-five people are arrested. They
burn the American flag and chant, ``Hang Rushdie!''
   Feb. 13 _ Police fire into a stone-throwing crowd protesting the
book in Srinagar, India, killing one person and wounding more than
60. The mob forces shops and businesses to close. Moslem students
also march in several Pakistani cities.
   Feb. 14 _ Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini decrees a ``death
sentence'' for Rushdie. ``Whoever is killed doing this (killing
Rushdie) will be regarded as a martyr and will go directly to
heaven,'' Khomeini tells would-be assassins. Rushdie says, ``I wish
I had written a more critical book.'' Scotland Yard gives him police
protection.
   Feb. 15 _ Rushdie's 11-city U.S. tour, coinciding with the U.S.
publication of the book, is canceled after an Iranian cleric puts a
$2.6 million price on his head. The bounty is later doubled. Rushdie
goes into hiding with his wife.
   Feb. 16 _ Waldenbooks, the nation's largest bookseller, orders
the $19.95 book off its shelves out of fear that threats of violence
might extend to its employees. It sells the book on request. The B.
Dalton and Barnes &amp; Noble chains, which have more than 1,250 stores,
later pull the book from their shelves.
   Feb. 18 _ Rushdie says he regrets ``the distress that publication
has occasioned,'' but the Iranian news agency says the apology isn't
enough to rescind the death sentence. Khomeini tells Moslems: ``Send
him to hell.''
   Feb. 20 _ The 12 members of the European Common Market countries
recall their ambassadors to Iran. Britain, which reopened its
embassy in Iran in November after a 17-month break, says it will
close its operation again in Tehran.
   Feb. 21 _ Iran retaliates by recalling all its ambassadors to the
Common Market countries. President Bush says the call for Rushdie's
execution is ``deeply offensive.''
   Feb. 22 _ Hundreds of authors march outside the Iranian Mission
to the United Nations as outraged writers step up their protests
over the reaction to the book. ``You will have to kill us all,''
says Boston author James Carroll in a remark aimed at Khomeini. B.
Dalton and Barnes &amp; Noble reverse their decision to pull the book.
   Feb. 24 _ In Bombay, India, street protests against the novel
left at least nine people dead and 40 injured. Initial news reports
said up to 12 died in protests over the book, but a police
commissioner, S.M. Shangari, said eight people died in the rioting
and one man died later in the hospital. Peaceful protest also were
reported in New Delhi, Calcutta and several other Indian cities.
   Feb. 25 _ British Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe today said
Austria, Finland ``and a number of other countries'' he didn't
identify have agreed to join the 12 Common Market nations in
withdrawing their ambassadors from Iran to protest Tehran's death
threat against Rushdie.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
