<DOCNO> AP890225-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 1357EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Miners     02-25 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Miners,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Publishes Report on 1981 Mine Killings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An official newspaper on Saturday published
a rare account of the police shooting of nine miners, the bloodiest
confrontation during a 1981 crackdown that suppressed the Solidarity
trade movement.
   The killings near the southern city of Katowice have become a
symbol of the brutality of the effort to suppress the Soviet bloc's
only independent trade movement.
   ``In order that wounds could cure completely, it is necessary to
expose them so that we could know all the truth about how they
originated and how they were cured,'' said the article in the weekly
Odrodzenie (Rebirth).
   The Dec. 16, 1981 battle began when miners went on strike to
protest authorities' attempt to quash Solidarity in a martial law
decree.
   The article quotes witnesses who described how police entered the
Wujek mine in a tank and armored personnel carriers and attacked the
miners with tear gas, water cannons and grenades.
   ``We saw the tank enter the mine's ground, breaking the barricade
we had erected from pipes and transport wagons, and under its cover
a wave of blue uniforms poured into the yard,'' the article quoted
Kazimierz Rembilas, a former mine employee, as saying.
   ``Then shots were fired. In the noise and chaos one could not see
who was shooting and from which direction.
   ``There was a moment of shock. I heard cries: `They are killed.'
Even then I could not believe they were shooting at us,'' he was
quoted as saying.
   The article interviewed Roza Czekalska, whose husband was one of
the miners killed.
   ``He (her husband) never got involved in politics. But he was
always going together with others in Solidarity. I still can't
understand how they could shoot at Polish miners,'' she was quoted
as saying.
   The weekly said two social commIttees in Katowice are seeking
permission to erect a monument to the victims of the Wujek mine.
   Until now, the Wujek mine incident has been virtually taboo for
the official media and an embarrassment for authorities who have
justified the military crackdown by saying it was necessary to avoid
some greater unspecified tragedy.
   Odrodzenie is one of many official newspapers now exploring
sensitive issues in Polish history.
   Last week, it published a Polish Red Cross report on the massacre
of more than 4,000 PolIsh officers in the Katyn forest during World
II. The Red Cross report implicitly pinned responsibility on the
Soviet Union.
   Polish and Soviet history books have long maintained Hitler's
army was responsible for the murder of the officers.
</TEXT>
