<SECOND>AM-Congress-Sudan,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Call for Cease-Fire in Civil War</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eleven members of Congress appealed Saturday
for a cease-fire in Sudan's civil war so that food aid and other
humanitarian relief efforts can be expedited.
   The action followed testimony at a Senate hearing Thursday
indicating that hundreds of thousands of civilians may die this year
unless shipments of food and medicine are allowed to reach needy
Sudanese before the onset of the rainy season weeks from now makes
shipments difficult or impossible.
   The lawmakers voiced their appeal in telegrams sent to Sudanese
Prime Minister Sadiq al-Mahdi and Col. John Garang, leader of the
rebel Sudanese People's Liberation Movement.
   ``We call upon both parties to the war to adopt an immediate
temporary cease-fire to facilitate the delivery of food and other
humanitarian relief until the rainy season begins,'' the messages
said.
   Senators signing the telegrams included Claiborne Pell, D-R.I.,
chairman of the Foreign Relations Committee; Jesse Helms, R-N.C.,
the committee's ranking Republican; Paul Simon, D-Ill., chairman of
the panel's Africa subcommittee; and Nancy Landon Kassebaum, R-Kan.,
the subcommittee's ranking Republican.
   Also signing were Sens. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.; Gordon J.
Humphrey, R-N.H.; Richard G. Lugar, R-Ind.; Alan K. Simpson, R-Wyo.;
and Reps. Howard Wolpe, D-Mich.; Dan Burton, R-Ind.; and Frank R.
Wolf, R-Va.
