<SECOND>AM-Hirohito Remark,0175</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Zealand Minister Expresses Regret Over Defense Chief's Remarks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Zealand's foreign minister said Saturday he
regretted what he called ``rude'' remarks his nation's defense chief
made about the late Emperor Hirohito, the government said.
   New Zealand Defense Minister Bob Tizard said last month that
Hirohito, who died of cancer Jan. 7, should have been tried and
executed as a war criminal after World War II.
   Cedric Marshall, the foreign minister of New Zealand, told his
Japanese counterpart that ``he regrets the intemperate statements
made by some people about Japan and Emperor Showa,'' a ministry
statement said, referring to Hirohito by his posthumous name.
   Marshall, who was in Tokyo for Hirohito's funeral Friday,
``assured Uno that these rude remarks do not represent the views of
the government and people of New Zealand, and said that he hopes
these incidents will not impair the development of good bilateral
relations,'' the ministry said.
   Uno replied that he hoped to further strengthen ties between the
two countries, it said.
