<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 1504EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-WhitherLabor     02-25 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Whither Labor,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>After Tough Times, Labor Leaders See Better Days Ahead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAL HARBOUR, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lane Kirkland, full-time labor activist
and part-time philosopher, offered a surprisingly short answer when
asked last week to assess the state of the American labor movement.
   ``It's good,'' the president of the 14.1 million-member AFL-CIO
said with a smile as the federation's leadership held its annual
meeting.
   Some might disagree, but labor leaders are feeling more confident
these days, upbeat in the belief that a new president, tight labor
market and soaring corporate profits mean there are better days _
and contracts _ ahead.
   ``We've weathered tolerably well a period in which we've had a
difficult legislative and political and economic climate,'' Kirkland
said when asked to expand on his assessment.
   That was a not-so veiled swipe at the Reagan administration,
which union leaders consider the most anti-union of the century and
the cause of the trade deficit that has made imports more attractive
than U.S. products.
   But Kirkland and other labor leaders do not place the blame for
the declining stature of unions on Reagan alone, conceding that
labor has been slow to change its ways in a swiftly changing economy.
   ``A labor force has grown up around us that's new in many
respects and we have not yet organized it to the extent that we want
to and that we expect to be able to over the course of time,''
Kirkland said. ``We've been through cycles like this before in our
history and emerged stronger, and I think we will again.''
   Labor hopes to prove it is again a major force in the U.S.
workplace and economy by winning better wage agreements this year,
after several years of post-recession focus on job security.
   ``It's time that we share economically in the profits,'' said
Lynn Williams, president of the United Steelworkers union, which saw
its membership and stature dive when the U.S. steel industry hit
hard times.
   Like some airline and other unions, the Steelworkers were forced
into concessions to keep jobs. The steel industry is not back to the
capacity it once had, but many companies are again profitable and
Williams is looking for a piece of prosperity.
   So are 675,000 communications and electrical workers at American
Telephone &amp; Telegraph and the regional phone companies _ the
so-called Baby Bells _ most of whose contracts expire this year.
   The Communication Workers of America and the International
Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, traditionally bitter enemies, for
the first time are negotiating jointly with the phone companies,
which have had huge profits since the AT&amp;T breakup.
   ``Wages that reflect the profitability of these companies,'' was
at the top of the list when CWA President Morton Bahr was asked
about objectives for the talks.
   Low unemployment has made competition for available workers keen,
slowly driving up wages. Most economists believe the rate of that
acceleration is due to quicken. The shortage of highly skilled
workers is particularly keen, something union negotiators hope to
parlay into significant wage gains in return for cooperative
labor-management efforts on training and retraining.
   Symbolically, labor sees in President Bush someone with whom it
disagrees on a number of issues but nonetheless a man without the
pro-business, anti-union ideological bent it perceived in Reagan.
The former president's firing of air traffic controllers in 1981,
labor leaders say, sent a signal to corporate boardrooms that union
bashing was in order.
   New Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole extolled the virtues of
collective bargaining during her visit with the labor leaders last
week, drawing kudos from the union officials despite some obvious
differences on issues.
   Organized labor also is looking to redirect its organizing
efforts to reverse a slide that has seen union representation of the
American workforce drop below 17 percent.
   A report on that subject was to be the highlight of the AFL-CIO
meeting, but the committee working on the project was unable to
reach consensus on proposals that could include revolutionary _ some
involved prefer the word evolutionary _ changes in union control
over individual locals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890225-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 1506EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-CalifDrought Bjt   02-25 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Calif Drought, Bjt,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Prepares For Third Dry Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN GRUBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With every passing day of blue skies,
water experts are growing more and more pessimistic that the state
can avoid an unprecedented third year of drought that would lead to
strict water rationing.
   ``After the dry January, a lot of my optimism faded,'' said Bob
Vasconcellos, resources and planning manager for the San Francisco
Water Department.
   ``I'm preparing for another year of this. January is normally the
wettest month in most areas. If you don't get the rain in January,
your chances (of recovery) are pretty slim.''
   As of Feb. 1, statewide precipitation for the winter was 35
percent below average, runoff was 55 percent below normal, and
reservoirs were only about 40 percent full. With each additional dry
week, the chances for recovery grow more slim.
   Weekend skiers find the mountains covered with a powdery snow.
Shrunken reservoirs reveal bare terraces of sand; rivers run in
ever-smaller channels through bone-dry rock beds. Forests are
spotted orange-red with dying trees, and anxious farmers watch their
tractors kick up dust where there should be mud.
   Unless California gets significant precipitation in the next few
weeks, officials say, much of the state will suffer hardships
rivaling those of the 1976-77 drought, when the state economy lost
$2.4 billion. The only area that will probably escape the most
stringent rationing is Southern California.
   ``The worst case would put us back where we were in '77, the last
big drought,'' said Gayle Montgomery, spokesman for the East Bay
Municipal Utility District in Oakland.
   ``That means loss of landscaping, pretty severe cutbacks in all
ways. ... It is no a pleasant thing to go through.''
   The East Bay district, like the San Francisco Water Department
across the bay, implemented 25 percent mandatory water rationing
last year. With an eye on their shrinking Sierra Nevada reservoirs,
both agencies are drafting further cutbacks.
   They are not alone. Depending on the severity of a continued
drought, a survey by the Department of Water Resources of 112
agencies found 60 to 76 plan mandatory rationing, up from 27
agencies in 1988.
   ``If this year is as critical as it was the last two years, there
will be considerable water rationing throughout California,'' said
Bill Helms of the Water Resources Department.
   Growers in the fertile San Joaquin Valley, facing cutbacks in
state water allocations of up to 40 percent and cuts in federal
allocations of up to 50 percent, are preparing to idle fields and
grow less thirsty and less profitable crops. The cutback in federal
Central Valley Project water is only the second in the project's
54-year history.
   Jason Peltier, manager of the Central Valley Project Water
Association, said a third drought year could cost agribusiness $1
billion in lost crops and up to $3 billion in losses in labor,
processing, packaging, transportation and other agriculture-related
industries.
   Most cities won't determine exact rationing plans until April,
the official end of the rainy season. Water experts say the outlook
could still improve, recalling Northern California floods in
Februrary 1986. But pessimism is growing.
   The San Francisco Water Department, which serves 2.1 million
people in San Francisco and the Silicon Valley, is developing
drought plans ranging from voluntary conservation to 35 percent
mandatory cuts.
   People in Southern California could fare much better, thanks to
diversified water supplies from the Owens Valley, the State Water
Project and a surplus of Colorado River water.
   ``The way things look right now, we should have enough water for
the coming year,'' said Tim Skrove, spokesman for the Metropolitan
Water District, which wholesales 2 million acre-feet to 14.5 million
people in Los Angeles, Ventura, Orange, San Diego, Riverside and San
Bernardino counties.
   ``We're still a little bit dry, but not nearly as bad as Northern
California,'' said Greg Starmack, spokesman for the San Diego County
Water Authority. The agency may seek voluntary conservation, but
primarily to reduce heavy demand on its delivery system during peak
hours.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
