<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia     02-25 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>Serbians Ask For Weapons Amid Protests; Gov't Pledges More Troops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SLOBODAN LEKIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Serbians asked authorities Saturday
for weapons to defend themselves amid growing protests by the ethnic
Albanian majority in Kosovo province. Officials announced they were
sending more troops and police.
   Tens of thousands of ethnic Albanians have walked off their jobs
since Monday, shutting down shops, schools and public
transportation. They are protesting a constitutional change and
demanding the resignation of the provincial Communist Party chief.
   ``We are threatened,'' said a statement from a group of Serbian
activists in Kosovo Polje, a Pristina suburb.
   The activists demanded the government introduce ``extraordinary
measures'' in Kosovo, an autonomous province in the republic of
Serbia.
   ``If they don't want to introduce martial law, then they should
give us arms to defend ourselves with because the situation is
critical,'' said Kosta Bulatovuc, a local Serbian leader, at the
meeting.
   Later Saturday, Yugoslavia's government said it would send more
troops and police to the province to protect ``the functioning of
vital services,'' the state-run Tanjug news service reported.
   ``The undertaking of other measures ... is also considered,'' the
report said without elaboration.
   The number of additional security forces was not disclosed.
   The action by was still one step away from the introduction of
martial law, decreed in 1981 after nine people were killed in ethnic
rioting.
   The protests began Monday at the Trepca mine, where about 1,300
lead and zinc miners, some on a hunger strike, remained in their
pits for a sixth day.
   Thirty miners were hospitalized Saturday with exhaustion, and 60
asked for medical aid at the mine, Tanjug said.
   Riza Muslimi, a spokesman for the striking miners, said they have
stashed two tons of explosives underground, but he would not say
whether they intended to use them to demolish the shaft if their
demands were not met.
   The protesters have condemned Serbia's drive to gain greater
control over Kosovo by changing the constitution, fearing they would
lose the wide autonomy granted to them in 1974. They also demand the
resignation of provincial party leader Rahman Morina, whom they
consider an ally of Serbian leaders aiming for more control over
Kosovo.
   The constitutional change would give Serbia greater control over
its two provinces, Kosovo and Vojvodina, and increase its powers
over defense and state security. The proposed change was approved by
Serbia on Thursday, but the amendments must also be approved by the
provincial assemblies.
   Serbian leaders say they must have more control in Kosovo to
protect the mainly Christian Slav minority from alleged persecution
by predominantly Moslem ethnic Albanians, who make up 85 percent of
the province's population.
   Saip Ljatifi, director of the Golesh magnesite mine, said his 360
striking ethnic Albanian miners ``would prefer to die rather than
repeat the experience'' of direct Serbian rule.
   In November, up to 100,000 ethnic Albanians demonstrated in
Pristina for five days to protest the dismissal of senior provincial
officials as demanded by Serbia's leaders.
   Tanjug said that Yugoslav leaders have told the protesters the
proposed constitutional changes do not mean the reduction of
Kosovo's autonomy feared by ethnic Albanians.
</TEXT>
