<FIRST>r a AM-RainPrayer     02-25 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rain Prayer,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Dakota Governor Calls For Prayer For Rain</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Calif Drought, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET BROKAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PIERRE, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. George Mickelson is asking churchgoers
in the state to offer a special prayer for rain next month to break
the drought that's parched much of the state since 1987.
   ``I think the focus of this is on the devastation that this
situation has for the families that depend on moisture for livestock
and crop production in this state,'' the governor said Friday.
   Mickelson proclaimed Palm Sunday, March 19, as a special day of
prayer for the farmers, ranchers, small business owners and others
harmed by the dry spell.
   Most South Dakota farm families survived the first full year of
drought last year, but ``a second year would be devastating,'' he
said.
   The dry conditions have eased in the eastern parts of the state,
Mickelson said, but the central and western portions of South Dakota
are still in the midst of mild to severe drought.
   ``I would give almost anything to make sure that we don't repeat
what happened last year with regard to the drought,'' he said.
``There isn't a day that goes by in my life but what I do not
continue to be concerned about the situation that we are in.''
   The federal government responded swiftly to provide aid to
farmers last year when many states were dry, but South Dakota might
find it tougher to get federal assistance this year if fewer states
are hit with drought, the governor said.
   Besides hurting farmers, another dry year year also could spark
more forest fires like the blazes that hit last summer in the Black
Hills, and could keep levels in state reservoirs below normal, he
said.
</TEXT>
