<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 1548EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-FloridaCold     02-25 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Florida Cold,0691</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cold Brings Record Lows, One Death, Crop Damage To Sunshine State</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold wave that stunned the Deep South broke low
temperature records all across Florida on Saturday, and an elderly
woman froze to death in an unheated home in the northern part of the
Sunshine State.
   Farther north, a powerful storm that dumped as much as 2 feet of
snow on the middle Atlantic states on Friday buffeted the New
England coast with wind up to 52 mph and snow while moving away
toward Nova Scotia.
   The arctic air that poured into Florida sent the mercury plunging
from the Panhandle all the way to Key West, the southern-most point
on the continental United States.
   Florida's rich citrus growing region reported minor crop damage
after the second night of record cold.
   But the cold snap was expected to ease slightly and the trend was
to warmer temperatures by Sunday night, said National Weather
Service forecaster Fred Gonzalez.
   ``The worst is over,'' he said.
   Florida's lowest temperature overnight was a record 18 degrees in
the northern part of the state at the capital city of Tallahassee.
   Other records in the state were 28 at Apalachicola, 29 at Daytona
Beach, 35 at Fort Lauderdale, 35 at Fort Myers, 36 at Hollywood, 24
at Jacksonville, 51 at Key West, 37 at Miami, 39 at Miami Beach, 30
at Orlando, 27 at Pensacola, 31 at Tampa and 35 at West Palm Beach.
In neighboring Alabama, Mobile tied its record of 27 and Montgomery
tied its record of 22.
   But while Florida shivered, Dodge City, Kan., posted a record
high Saturday of 80 degrees.
   Just outside the capital in Miccosukee, police said a 65-year-old
woman froze to death in her unheated home. She was discovered
unconscious by a concerned neighbor and paramedics could not revive
her.
   ``This is an extremely rare occurrence in Leon County,''
sheriff's spokesman Dick Simpson said.
   The death prompted deputies to visit other unheated homes late
Friday to check on residents, he said.
   In other cities around Florida, shelters filled up with homeless
people who usually sleep on the streets in more hospitable weather.
   In Broward County the Salvation Army set up cots in the dining
room and put people on floors and in hallways to make certain no one
was left out in the cold.
   The biggest economic worry caused by the cold was in the Central
Florida citrus belt, which suffered a diastrous freeze in 1985, but
the region appeared to have avoided the worst this time.
   ``Florida citrus growers for the most part escaped signficant
damage from Friday night and Saturday morning's freezing
temperatures, which dipped into almost all of the state's citrus
growing areas,'' said Dick Whalley of the Florida Citrus Mutual, a
growers cooperative, in Lakeland.
   He said extended cold in some low-lying areas probably harmed new
blossoms, but it will be weeks before the full damage can be
determined.
   Many farmers battled the frost with smudge pots or sprinklers.
   ``I've been out all night,'' Jerry Chicone, a partner in Chicone
Groves west of Orlando, said Saturday morning. Damage to his groves
was minimal, he said.
   Some farmers were less fortunate, however.
   David Coney, an Alachua County blueberry grower, estimated his
loss at 90 percent. Coney said a neighbor who grows apples also lost
a substantial amount of fruit.
   ``I had some early-ripening varieties and they got clobbered,''
Coney said. ``That's just one of the risk factors in farming. If I
wanted a sure winner, I'd play the lottery.''
   In Miami, Gary Mehalik, spokesman for the Florida Power &amp; Light
Co., which serves 3 million South Florida customers, said the
utility hit a record for power-use between 7 and 8 a.m. Saturday, a
time when commercial and industrial demand is low.
   ``Eighty-two percent of our customers have electric heat,'' he
said. ``That uses up a lot of electricity when people roll out of
bed in the morning and turn on the heat.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
