<SECOND>AM-Sudan-Government,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime Minister To Form Broad-Based Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sudanese Cabinet met in an emergency
session Saturday and ordered Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi to form a
new broad-based government, the information minister said.
   Minister Beshir Omar did not say when the new government would be
formed.
   Last week, the military gave el-Mahdi a week to either resign or
reform his government and seek peace with the rebels fighting it.
   El-Mahdi later said he was told by the army that the one-week
deadline was not final. He will address the political situation
Monday in a speech to Parliament, Omar said.
   Omar did not say whether the nation's Democratic Unionist Party,
which quit the government to protest el-Mahdi's policies, would be
invited to join the new government.
   The party quit in December because el-Mahdi refused to endorse a
tentative peace agreement the party signed with the rebel Sudan
People's Liberation army.
   On Saturday, the party issued a statement urging el-Mahdi to form
a new government as a gesture of good will and immediately carry out
the peace plan.
   The rebels took up arms in 1983, and have demanded economic and
administrative reforms. In the past few months, they have taken over
several strategic government garrisons in the south.
