<HEAD>Judge Performs Wedding, Gives Juror 10-minute Honeymoon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A juror took his courtroom seat with a carnation
and a newlywed's smile after a judge eager to start a trial
performed a wedding, gave the couple a 10-minute honeymoon and
struck the opening gavel.
   Supreme Court Justice Martin Stecher was exasperated when a juror
announced his wedding day was set for Feb. 17, when trial was
finally to begin after two delays in a $20 million lawsuit against
the city.
   The trial was postponed once because the wife of an attorney was
having a Caesarean section, and a second time because another lawyer
was closing a house-buying deal, the New York Post reported.
   Then the juror, a man in his 30s who was not otherwise
identified, asked that the Feb. 17 date be set aside too so he could
get married.
   ``No way,'' the judge said. ``Tell the juror to bring his bride,
a license, two witnesses _ and I'll marry them.''
