<SECOND>AM-BRF--Bomb Scare,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>Passenger Arrested After Unscheduled Landing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A charter flight carrying more than 350
people made an unscheduled landing at Indianapolis International
Airport Saturday after a passenger joked about having explosives,
authorities said.
   Anthony Glynn Pierson, 23, of Rochester Hill, Mich., was charged
with violating the false information act and making threats, said
Sgt. John Wheeler of the Indiana State Police. The charges carry a
penalty of up to five years in prison and a fine of $250,000.
   The L-1011 plane was searched, nothing was found, and passengers
reboarded and continued on to Cancun, Mexico, said Robert Spitler of
the Indianapolis Airport Authority.
   American Trans Air Flight 309 from Detroit was carrying 339
passengers and a crew of 12, according to John Ashton, the airline
security director.
   The FBI said Pierson told authorities he had told the flight
attendant he had prophylactics, but Wheeler said ``many witnesses
advised he stated he had plastic explosives.''
