<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 1657EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Mexico-Amnesty     02-25 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Amnesty,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>Struggle For Land Behind Political Imprisonment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the political prisoners being freed
under a new amnesty program were jailed in connection with the
bitter land battles that Amnesty International calls the prime cause
of human rights abuses in Mexico.
   About 90 percent of the cases involve land disputes, Luis Ortiz
Moasterio, the Interior Ministry's human rights director, told the
government news agency Notimex on Saturday.
   Mexico's turf battles usually pit land-hungry peasants against
powerful local property owners and the rural bosses. Human rights
groups say the authorities side with the big landowners and bosses.
   Under pressure from human rights activists, President Carlos
Salinas de Gortari said Thursday that he would free 403 prisoners,
one of them a prominent poet and activist who was released a day
later.
   Opposition figures welcomed the releases but demanded a
timetable, and said there were hundreds of other political prisoners
not involved in the amnesty program.
   Government officials, however, said they would work with state
officials to free another 400 prisoners.
   Amnesty International, the London-based human right organization,
has for years expressed concern about arbitrary detentions, torture
and killings of Mexican peasants and Indians.
   Many of the victims of human rights violations in Mexico ``were
active in groups pursuing objectives strongly opposed by local
landowners and by local and state government authorities,'' Amnesty
said in a 1986 report.
   The struggle for land often is a catalyst for opposition
political activism by peasants and Indians who feel the ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party has failed to make good on its
promises.
   The Mexican government has consistently denied the Amnesty
International reports and allegations by other human rights group.
   It continues to insist it has no political prisoners, despite the
amnesty program announced Thursday. Interior Secretary Fernando
Gutierrez Barrios has said the program is freeing people who
committed crimes for ``political or social'' reasons _ not political
prisoners.
   One of the more prominent prisoners involved in the amnesty is
poet Israel Gutierrez Hernandez, who worked with peasant groups
fighting for land rights in the north-central state of San Luis
Potosi. He had been cited by Amnesty International and several other
groups as a prisoner of conscience.
   Gutierrez Hernandez, 37, was freed on Friday after serving about
half of a 10-year sentence for robbery, criminal association and
possession of military weapons _ charges he denied.
   Officials have said about 10 of Mexico's 31 states are included
in the amnesty program.
   Rosario Ibarra de Piedra, Mexico's most prominent human rights
activist, said Saturday that peasant organizations in several states
have submitted lists of hundreds of prisoners to the government.
   The lists include people imprisoned in the states of Michoacan,
Veracruz, Chiapas and Oaxaca, she said in a telephone interview with
The Associated Press.
   Amnesty International has long monitored reports of human rights
violations in Mexico, particularly in rural areas. Its 1986 special
report concentrated on the southern states of Oaxaca and Chiapas,
where arable land is scarce, subsistence farming is a way of life
and some of Mexico's most violent land disputes occur.
   Authorities have said Oaxaca is not now part of the new amnesty
program because it has no political prisoners. The official list of
prisoners slated for release did not mention Chiapas and Interior
Ministry officials contacted Saturday did not know its status.
   Land reform was a bright promise of Mexico's 1910 revolution. But
after 74 years of redistribution, many peasants are still landless
or have seen their communal land taken away by large landholders.
Clouded titles and a creaky bureaucracy further entangle the
disputes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
