<FIRST>r a AM-RelativeShot     02-25 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Relative Shot,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police: Man Asked Aunt to Shoot Him, and She Did</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Beaird is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KEOKUK, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who told authorities he was hit by
random street gunfire actually had gotten drunk and persuaded his
68-year-old aunt to pull the trigger _ an incident police described
as ``stranger than fiction.''
   Eva Jean White was charged with assault Friday, accused of
wounding her nephew, John E. Lewis, 31, with pellets from a 2-gauge
shotgun.
   ``At first, she didn't think she had hit him. But it started
stinging a little bit, and then John decided he didn't want to be
shot near as bad as he said he did,'' said Police Maj. Kenneth
Beaird.
   Beaird said the woman deliberately aimed to the side when she
pulled the trigger Wednesday morning in the home the two share in
Keokuk. Lewis was struck by about 35 pieces of buckshot and has
since been released from a hospital.
   Lewis first claimed to have been shot while walking along a
street, minding his own business, authorities said.Police revised
the report to say that Lewis had ``solicited'' Ms. White to do the
shooting.
   ``By his admission to me, John is an alcoholic, and in a drunken
state, he was trying to find somebody to shoot him,'' Beaird said.
   ``Now this old woman, she's a crusty old gal. She finally says
she got tired of hearing him, so she said, `You want me to shoot you
in the backside, then get it downstairs in the basement,''' Beaird
said.
   He said Lewis was struck with fewer than a tenth of the pellets
in the charge, but that he was ``uncomfortable, so he had to come up
with some kind of story.''
   ``You've heard that the truth is stranger than fiction? It's
true,'' Beaird said. ``This is a wormy one.''
   Beaird said Lewis has sought counseling at a mental health center.
</TEXT>
