<FIRST>r i AM-NicaraguanCanal     02-25 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaraguan Canal,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan Official Says Canal Wouldn't Take Business From Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plan to build a canal across Nicaragua with
Japanese backing would not threaten a proposed second canal in
Panama, Nicaragua's finance minister was quoted as saying Saturday.
   ``It's a complementary idea,'' William Huper Arguell was quoted
as saying by the Kyodo News Service. ``The growing flow of East-West
and North-South commerce brings about a need now for various types
of routes.''
   Kyodo quoted Panama's acting president, Manuel Solis Palma, as
saying: ``Every country has a right to put forward whatever plan it
wants to.''
   Nicaragua proposed the canal earlier this month, and Kyodo said
studies are expected to take about three years to complete. The
agency quoted Huper as saying construction could take up to 10 years.
   Huper and Solis attended Friday's funeral of Emperor Hirohito,
who died last month of cancer.
   Huper was quoted as saying he plans to meet with Japanese firms
and business organizations to drum up interest in the mammoth
project before leaving Tokyo on Wednesday.
   He would not elaborate on the composition of a private delegation
of Japanese scientists and builders who are scheduled to visit
Nicaragua next month in connection with the plan.
   Japanese officials have said the Tokyo government, which supports
Panama's plan for a second canal linking the Atlantic and Pacific,
does not intend to become involved in the Nicaraguan project.
