<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 1711EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Auction     02-25 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Auction,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sold! L.A.-Moscow Auction Draws Bilingual Bids</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bidders in Los Angeles vied with a studio audience
in Moscow on Saturday to buy crystal, paintings and other items in a
unique televised charity auction to raise funds for earthquake
victims.
   The broadcast, the first of its kind in the Soviet Union, was
beamed by satellite to socialist countries, Western Europe, the
United States and Japan.
   It was sponsored by Intermedbio, a joint U.S.-Soviet venture that
promotes business contacts between the two countries, and
GostelRadio, the state-run radio and television network.
   Initial bidding, via live satellite link-up, pit a studio
audience in Los Angeles against a Moscow audience of Soviet and
Western businessmen, diplomats and foreign representatives of
Soviet-based foreign firms.
   Members of the general public were not invited to the Moscow
audience, which was held at Goskino, the state cinema.
   The broadcast began at 10 p.m. and had raised more than $25,000
when it ended at midnight, officials said.
   The auction was held on behalf of those hurt or left homeless by
two earthquakes, one in Armenia Dec. 7 and another in Tadjikistan on
Jan. 24. The quake in Armenia claimed about 25,000 lives, injured at
least 19,000 and left hundreds of thousands homeless. The quake in
Tadjikistan killed about 250 people.
   Early bidding, all in dollars, raised about $10,000 in 45 minutes
with buyers taking home crystal dishes and a set of paintings by
Armenian children that brought $3,000 from a Los Angeles man.
   The bidding went dry, however, when the really expensive items
went on the block, including seven thoroughbred horses and a Soviet
tractor.
   Bidding on the tractor opened at $8,000, but it was unsold
because only one bid was received _ $2,100 from a Los Angeles man.
   ``Apparently Americans don't buy tractors on Saturday,'' the
auctioneer joked.
   The official Tass news agency said before the bidding began that
a helicopter would be put on the block as well as the world's
largest carpet made in Armenia. However, neither item was listed in
the catalogue.
   Bidding in the two-hour auction picked up again when items such
as Soviet-made watches went on the block at $50 to $100.
   ``It's a bargain,'' the auctioneer said, urging the Los Angeles
audience to buy.
   After the initial bidding, viewers at home were able to call in
bids on items not taken by the studio audiences, either by
telephoning their local studio or by facsimile or telex.
   ``The aim of the charity TV auction ... is to bring foreign
currency into the aid fund for quake victims in Armenia and
Tadjikstan,'' Tass said.
   Damage from the Armenian earthquake has been estimated at $16.2
billion, not including the long-term medical requirements of
survivors, according to Armenian officials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
