<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Angola     02-25 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa-Angola,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Countries Reaffirm Commitment To Treaty Despite Disputes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angola, Cuba and South Africa
on Saturday reaffirmed their commitment to a regional peace treaty
and promised not to let the actions of two guerrilla groups endanger
the pact, a news agency reported.
   The countries wrapped up three days of talks in Luanda, Angola,
that were held to discuss developments since the peace agreement was
signed in New York in December.
   Under the U.S.-mediated treaty, Cuba has agreed to a phased
withdrawal of its 50,000 soldiers in Angola, who support the Marxist
government in its war against the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola guerrilla movement.
   In return, South Africa pledged to halt aid to the rebel group
and grant independence to Namibia, also known as South-West Africa.
   Angola has alleged that South African soldiers entered its
territory two weeks ago in support of the rebels. South Africa has
denied the allegation.
   Meanwhile, South Africa says Angola has allowed guerrillas of the
South-West Africa People's Organization to maintain bases in
southern Angola near the Namibian border. That group is supposed to
move its military bases northward under the agreement.
   The organization has been fighting for independence in Namibia
since 1966 and is the favorite in elections scheduled for later this
year.
   Angola agreed to use its influence with Namibian rebels, and
South Africa pledged to do likewise with the Angolan insurgents in
order to ensure the peace agreement, the independent South African
Press Association reported from Luanda.
   In a joint statement at the end of Saturday's meeting, South
Africa, Angola and Cuba ``reaffirmed once again their commitment to
comply strictly with the agreement,'' the news agency said.
   Neither guerrilla movement was included in the peace agreement,
although the South-West Africa People's Organization has announced a
cease-fire. The National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
has continued its 13-year-old war against the Angolan government.
   The next meeting between the three countries will be held in Cuba
in March.
</TEXT>
