<FIRST>r a AM-ChurchClosings     02-25 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Church Closings,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Detroit Archbishop Decries City Council's Hearing On Closings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City Council is violating the principle of
church-state separation by scheduling a public hearing on the
Archdiocese of Detroit's plans to close 30 churches in the city,
Cardinal Edmund Szoka said.
   The March 9 hearing also ``raises questions of anti-Catholicism,
as no other religious denomination has ever been the subject of a
City Council hearing,'' the archdiocese said Friday in a statement.
   Council members denied Szoka's charges and said they scheduled
the hearing to determine the effect of the planned closings on
Detroit neighborhoods.
   ``I think it's terrible to say we're anti-Catholic just because
we're concerned about the departure of community resources and
community services,'' said Councilwoman Maryann Mahaffey, who
sponsored the resolution calling for the hearing.
   ``We're not saying they're wrong,'' she said. ``But when an
organization leaves and their services close down, the question is:
What thought are they giving as to who's going to meet the need when
they go? Who's going to pick up the pieces?''
   Archdiocesan officials will not participate in the hearing, and
Szoka has asked the council to rescind the resolution, spokesman Jay
Berman said. Jews, Lutherans and Methodists have closed more
sanctuaries in Detroit over the years than has the archdiocese, he
added.
   ``None of those faiths were singled out for a hearing,'' Berman
said. ``And when you are singled out, that question (of
anti-Catholicism) just has to be one of the questions asked.''
   Szoka announced Jan. 8 that the archdiocese would close 30
churches because of low membership, aging buildings, low income and
a shortage of priests. Those churches were scheduled to close by
June 30, although some have said they might appeal to the Vatican.
   The Rev. Norman Thomas, pastor of Sacred Heart Church in Detroit
and an opponent of the closings, said the archdiocese's reaction
indicated Szoka had prejudged the hearing.
   ``I think it shows the defensiveness of the cardinal to the whole
question of church closings,'' Thomas said. ``Why wouldn't they send
people to the hearing if they think (the closings) are such a good
idea?''
</TEXT>
