<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Schiotz     02-25 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Schiotz,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>First President of American Lutheran Church Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Fredrick is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Fredrick Axel Schiotz, the
first president of the American Lutheran Church, died Saturday. He
was 87.
   Since retiring as head of the 2.5 million-member denomination in
1971, Schiotz had taught at seminaries and colleges and carried out
special tasks for the ALC and Lutheran World Relief.
   He died at Marti Luther Manor, a nursing home. No cause of death
was made public.
   Schiotz, a native of Chicago, was elected president of the
Evangelical Lutheran Church in 1954. He worked in merger
negotiations that led to the formation in 1960 of the ALC and was
elected to a six-year term as its first president. He was re-elected
in 1966.
   The ALC, based in Minneapolis, merged with the Lutheran Church in
America and the Association of Evangelical Lutheran Churches in 1987
to form the Evangelical Lutheran Church in America, which has its
headquarters in Chicago.
   Schiotz, who earned a master's degree in sacred theology from
Luther Seminary in 1932, served from 1938 to 1945 as executive
director of the Student Service Commission of the ALC. He was a
pastor in New York City for three years and then became executive
secretary of the National Lutheran Council's Commission on Younger
Churches and Orphaned Missions.
   Schiotz helped organize the Lutheran World Federation at Lund,
Sweden, in 1947 and was elected its president in 1963 at Helsinki,
Finland. He filled that post through 1970 and continued as a member
of the federation's executive committee.
   In addition, Schiotz served on the executive committee of the
Lutheran Council in the United States and was a member of the
Central Committee of the World Council of Churches.
   Survivors include his wife, Dagny Aasen, two sons and a daughter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890225-0135 </DOCNO>
