<HEAD>Wife Of Jailed Czech Dissident Concerned About His Health</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 10-11, `Mrs. Havel...Havel said.' with five grafs
to UPDATE with Polish premier attending Havel's play. Pick up 12th pvs:
In a...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovak-Mood, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of Czechoslovakia's leading
dissident said in an interview broadcast Saturday that her husband
has fallen ill and may not be receiving adequate medical attention
in prison.
   The dissident, playwright Vaclav Havel, was sentenced Tuesday to
nine months in prison after being convicted of inciting citizens to
take part in a banned demonstration and obstructing police officers.
   His wife, Olga Havel, told Austrian radio she has not been
allowed to talk with her husband since he was detained in Prague
five weeks ago.
   His arrest caused widespread protests in Czechoslovakia. East
bloc and Western nations, including the United States, called for
his release.
   ``He is suffering from a series of health problems, and I deeply
fear for his health,'' Mrs. Havel said in the interview. ``In prison
they give only cold water, and there is no regular medical care.''
   She did not describe the ailments of Havel, 52, who had spent a
total of four years in jail for his activism before his latest
arrest.
   Mrs. Havel said no evidence was presented in court that her
husband incited people or ignored appeals to end the demonstration
in Prague's Wenceslas Square. ``The sentence was a political
decision,'' she said.
   Prosecutor Karel Florian had demanded a one-year sentence for
Havel and a $2,500 fine. The presiding judge gave the dissident a
nine-month sentence, which Havel instantly appealed. No fine was
imposed.
   Havel defiantly declared during his trial that he was not guilty
of inciting people to attend a Jan. 15 commemoration for Jan Palach,
a student who burned himself to death 20 years ago to protest the
1968 Soviet-led invasion that ended reforms of Communist Party chief
Alexander Dubcek.
   In Warsaw, Poland, meanwhile, Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F.
Rakowski and leading opposition activists both attended the opening
of two of Havel's plays.
   Adam Michnik, a historian and leading Polish political theorist
who has spent years in jail for his writings, jumped on the stage
after the performance and appealed to Czech authorities to release
Havel.
   Michnik called on the ``competent authorities (in Czechoslovakia)
to stop repression'' and urged the Czech leadership to ``take the
same road as other East European countries are taking _
reconciliation with the nation.''
   Rakowski stood throughout most of Michnik's speech and then
quietly left the theater. Most of the 500 people who were in
attendance stood and applauded Michnik's appeal.
   The Powszechny Theater was packed for the performance of
``Audience'' and ``Protest,'' two one-act plays that examine the
choices ordinary people face when confronting authorities in
totalitarian countries.
   In a related development Saturday, 25O young people called for
the release of political prisoners at the first joint meeting of the
Independent Peace Association and the official Czechoslovak
Socialist Youth Union.
   Participants said they observed a minute of silence in Palach's
memory.
   The Independent Peace Association was set up last year,
advocating the establishment of alternatives to military service in
Czechoslovakia and protesting violations of human rights.
   Founding member Jana Petrova was sentenced to nine months' jail
on charges of hooliganism Wednesday, a day after Havel was sentenced.
   Tomas Tvaroch, another group member, told the meeting two
separate petitions have been circulated around Prague to collect
signatures for courts where Havel and Petrova will have their
sentences appealed at an unspecified date, sources said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
