<FIRST>r p AM-Governors-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0513 02-25 0949</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Governors-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0513,920</SECOND>
<HEAD>By and Large, Governors Not Calling for New Taxes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 12th graf pvs, bgng: ``Democrat Richard...''
to add Cuomo cancellation; picks up 13th graf pvs, bgng: ``One Republican...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With few exceptions, the nation's governors are
respecting President Bush's ``no new taxes'' pledge and holding off
on calls for raising revenue to reduce the federal deficit.
   ``I don't see how he can abandon his `read my lips' promise this
early in his term,'' said Gov. Bill Clinton of Arkansas, chairman of
the Democratic Governors Association.
   ``He's so committed on that (resisting new taxes), it would
destroy his credibility as president,'' said Democratic Gov. Rudy
Perpich of Minnesota.
   An Associated Press survey of governors as they prepared for
their annual midwinter Washington meeting, which began Saturday,
also found most state executives urging the new president to use his
office to promote higher educational standards and innovation.
   That kind of leadership rather than massive increases in federal
funds was cited as the best way for Bush to achieve his goal of
becoming the ``education president.''
   ``I think the main thing the president of the United States
should do is to highlight education and make it the issue,'' said
Republican Gov. Thomas Kean of New Jersey. ``He's got the bully
pulpit. We want to know, all of us, that education is (at) the top
of the national agenda.''
   The governors were asked if they thought proposals to raise
federal revenue should be on the table when the White House and
Congress try to reach an agreement on how to reduce the federal
deficit.
   They also were asked how they would advise Bush to fulfill his
vow to be the ``education president.''
   During President Reagan's first term, governors often were in the
forefront of those urging the White House to consider new revenues
to deal with growing budget shortfalls. But Reagan held the line and
the governors dropped their appeals for tax increases during his
second term.
   Only a handful of governors urged Bush to consider new revenues.
   Among them was Democrat Steve Cowper of Alaska, who said,
``Otherwise we can't ever get the budget balanced.''
   Democrat Richard Celeste of Ohio said new revenues ought to be on
the table ``but only if the president puts them there.''
   Democrat Mario Cuomo of New York canceled his trip to the NGA
meeting because of a dispute with South Carolina Gov. Carroll
Campbell, a Republican, over how to deal with the federal deficit.
   Cuomo and Campbell head an NGA task force on the federal budget
and were to have presented a proposal to their fellow governors on
the deficit. That came apart last week when Campbell objected to
Cuomo's talk about a ``trigger-tax'' provision that would be
included in the proposal.
   Cuomo spokesman Gary Fryer said a deficit reduction plan probably
would be presented to the governors at their May meeting in Chicago.
   One Republican, Gov. Edward D. DiPrete of Rhode Island, predicted
Bush would find a way to back away from his pledge of no new taxes.
   ``I don't say Bush is going to lead the charge for a tax
increase, but sooner or later, some innocuous study (recommending a
tax increase) is going to come from someplace,'' he said.
``Probably, President Bush is going to say, `I don't like it, but if
that's what everybody else thinks, I won't stand in your way.'''
   Other Republicans stood firmly behind the president.
   ``There's no point in putting any new taxes on the table,'' said
Kean.
   ``I think he's taking the rght attitude,'' said Republican Gov.
Bob Martinez of Florida. ``He's going there without any tax thoughts
of revenue enhancement.''
   ``President Bush clearly feels that increased taxes are not
needed to reduce the federal deficit,'' said Republican Gov. Stan
Stephens of Montana. ``We support him in that position and encourage
Congress to look at the spending side and improved government
efficiency.''
   ``I don't think tax increases are the answer,'' said Republican
Gov. Michael Castle of Delaware. ``I think the time has come in this
country for Congress and the White House to stop talking about hard
decisions and start making some.''
   Gov. James Thompson of Illinois, a Republican who is the senior
governor in terms of length of service, said that while federal
funds for school meals and to help disadvantaged children are
important ``even more important is for the president to rally the
nation to a call for a better-educated youth who must compete in the
modern world with other nations.''
   Democrat Booth Gardner of Washington said the states and federal
government ``must build a new partnership that will make early
childhood education and development a national priority.''
   Gardner said he supported administration efforts to encourage
community service and ``I am also urging the Bush administration to
allow greater flexibility in regulations which will allow our
teachers and schools to be more creative and innovative.''
   Democratic Gov. Mike Sullivan of Wyoming was skeptical about what
Bush could do for education ``given the very pressing budget issues
facing us. Certainly, our efforts to cut the budget deficit will be
integrally related to our efforts to improve education, at least as
far as spending goes.''
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, whom Bush defeated for the
presidency, cited three propoals he had made during that campaign: a
teaching excellence fund to help young people studying to become
teachers; field centers to encourage teachers to sharpen their
skills, and a federally backed college loan program.
   Republican Terry Branstad of Iowa urged Bush to ``convene a
national conference on educational excellence and to provide
additional support for students' access to higher education.''
</TEXT>
