<FIRST>r a AM-CarouselAuction     02-25 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Carousel Auction,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carousel Art Sets Auction Record</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new record for carousel art was set Saturday
when a hand-carved rooster sold for $148,500 at auction, Sotheby's
said.
   The sale, which featured elaborately hand-carved wooden horses,
zebras, giraffes, chariots and pigs, fetched a total of $1.3
million, said Diana Levitt, the auction house's director of
corporate affairs.
   ``There were a lot of smiles today,'' she said. ``These pieces
bring back so many childhood and adult memories.''
   The white rooster, replete with a green and black saddle, brought
the highest bid at the sale, Levitt said. The rare carving by
woodcarver Gustav Dentzel dates back to about 1895 and is one of
four known to exist.
   There was applause at the auction when bidders learned a carousel
in Asbury Park, N.J. would not have to be dismantled and sold piece
by piece, the spokeswoman said.
   The owner of the 1895 carousel had wanted to sell it intact for
at least $900,000. But, when there were no bids for the entire
carousel, seven carved horses were sold individually before it was
announced that a group calling itself the Friends of Asbury Park was
intervening to save the carousel.
   The carousel has 68 horses and animals and two chariots.
   She said that buyers of individual horses from the Asbury Park
carousel will be allowed to cancel their purchase, if they choose,
so that the Palace Carousel can remain intact.
</TEXT>
