<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 2126EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Plane-Passengers 2ndLd-Writethru a0626 02-25 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plane-Passengers, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0626,0751</SECOND>
<HEAD>Passengers Continue Travels; Other Remain Behind</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Plane Emergency, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 11th graf, `United Airlines...', to CORRECT to 247 passengers
sted 274.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos HU11, HU12</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Passengers who survived United Airlines Flight
811 reached their destinations Saturday with vivid tales of being
``scared to death'' as dozens more chose to stay behind in Hawaii.
   ``It was a nightmare and I'm glad I got back on that plane today
because if I'd waited I don't know if I would have ever flown
again,'' said Cathy Mehan, of Washington, D.C., after she arrived in
New Zealand early Saturday.
   The fuselage of a United jumbo jet carrying 354 people ripped
open shortly after takeoff early Friday from Honolulu International
Aiport, and nine people were sucked from the plane 20,000 feet above
the Pacific Ocean.
   The crippled Boeing 747 made an emergency landing with a
10-foot-wide, 40-foot-high section torn from its right side.
   Rochelle Perel, 48, of Beverly Hills, Calif., was just an arms
length away from the gaping hole.
   ``The aircraft (section) was blown away and I noticed the wind,
the stars and the clouds,'' Perel said. ``It was an indication we
weren't going to make it, and it was very scary.''
   Enrique Reyes, 36, survived with ``$250 and the experience of a
lifetime.'' He was supposed to have taken a direct flight home to
Sydney, Australia, when he checked in at Los Angeles.
   The flight was apparently full, and a United employee offered him
$250 if he would take a seat aboard Flight 811, which was departing
later Thursday.
   Reflecting on his $250 bonus, Reyes said, ``It wasn't worth it.''
   Passengers held loved ones and prepared for the worst as the
plane headed back to Honolulu.
   ``I thought I was going to die,'' said Robert Molnar of Sydney,
who was returning from a Hawaiian honeymoon with his wife, Helen.
``I made a comment to my wife that we've only been married for three
weeks. What a way for it to end.''
   Others took snapshots including Beverley Nisbet, of Hastings, New
Zealand, who saw another passenger snapping pictures and decided it
would give her something to do.
   Nisbet thought she had taken only one picture, which looks toward
the front of the passenger cabin and shows the damaged interior. She
doesn't remember taking the second, which shows passengers wearing
life jackets braced against seats. The photographs were distributed
by The Associated Press.
   Paul Grigson of Sydney said passengers in the rear of the
aircraft were unaware of how serious the situation was.
   ``Most people thought it was just a window or something had gone
and they didn't realize how bad it was until they got off the
plane,'' Grigson said.
   ``Scared? Yeah, I was scared. Terrified. More scared now,
though,'' Grigson said.
   United Airlines said 247 of the 336 passengers from Flight 811
boarded a special flight Friday night for New Zealand and Australia.
Those who didn't want to fly right away were put up in hotels.
   Honolulu hospitals treated 27 people, mostly for minor injuries.
Five people remained hospialized Saturday.
   Leanne Devlin, 23, of Sydney, Australia, was among those who
decided to take the first flight home.
   ``I'm a bit jumpy about hopping back on, but there's no other way
to get home,'' Miss Devlin said.
   Early Saturday, 110 passengers from Flight 811 arrived at Aukland
International Airport in New Zealand aboard the special flight.
   Ms. Mehan remembered thinking during the ordeal: ``Am I gonna
make it? Am I gonna die? Am I gonna live? I didn't feel it was my
time to go, but I was just scared to death.''
   ``I'm surprised that we're here. I didn't feel like we were gonna
be here,'' Denise Brady of Denver said after arriving in Aukland.
   She said was ``a little jumpy'' getting back on an airplane.
   ``Everyone watched the safety film intently. Every head was
riveted to it,'' Ms. Brady said.
   Gill Perry of Colorado recalled how jubilant Flight 811's
passengers were when the plane landed in Honolulu.
   ``There was just great relief _ and disbelief,'' he said.
   ``Talking with other people sitting farther up in the plane, I
realize how close we came to dying,'' said John Peryer of Hastings,
New Zealand. ``I'm just thankful I'm back on the ground, but I'm
sorry for the ones that didn't make it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
