<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 2210EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-ShipDeaths 1stLd-Writethru a0506 02-25 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ship Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0506,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three South Korean Seamen Die of Oxygen Shortage</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three South Korean crewmen on a tanker died from
lack of oxygen while they were working near storage containers
filled with nitrogen gas, the coast guard said Sunday.
   The three were found Saturday inside a cargo tank of the
3,627-ton Panamanian-registered ship Shoko-maru, said a coast guard
duty officer. The ship was berthed at Kashima, northeast of Tokyo.
   The ship, with a crew of 18, arrived at the port earlier Saturday
carrying palm oil, and the accident occurred during unloading of the
oil, said the officer, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   He said some of the ship's storage containers were filled with
nitrogen gas after part of the oil was unloaded from the ship at the
port of Osaka, in western Japan, where the ship visited earlier.
   The officer said nitrogen gas generally is used to replace palm
oil while it is being removed from the storage containers to prevent
the oil from being spoiled by touching the air.
   But he said the storage area where the three Koreans were found
was empty.
   Local police and coast guard officials were investigating the
deaths.
</TEXT>
