<FIRST>r a AM-CowboysSale-Newspage     02-25 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cowboys Sale-Newspage,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dallas Cowboys Football Team Sold to Arkansas Millionaire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNE H. FREEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Sports Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>IRVING, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dallas Cowboys football team was sold
Saturday to an Arkansas millionaire, who immediately replaced Tom
Landry, the team's only coach in its 29-year history.
   Team owner H.R. ``Bum'' Bright sold the Cowboys to Jerry Jones,
46, of Little Rock, Ark. Jones' empire includes two oil and gas
exploration and production companies, Arkoma Exploration Co. and JMC
Exploration Co.
   Jones named his longtime friend, Jimmy Johnson, football coach at
the University of Miami, as head coach of the Cowboys. At Miami,
Johnson won the national championship in 1987.
   The sale price was not disclosed but it had been estimated at
$140 million.
   ``That's between Bum and me, but I don't mind telling you I'm
going to need some lead in my back pocket,'' Jones said at a news
conference. ``I'm going to leave Dallas lighter than when I came
in.''
   The Cowboys finished with a 3-13 record in 1988. Landry's record
with the Cowboys was 250-162-6.
   Landry, 64, set an National Football League record with 20
consecutive winning seasons from 1966 through 1985. He is third on
the NFL's all-time victory list behind George Halas and Don Shula.
   Landry had one year left on his contract at $800,000. He joined
the Cowboys in 1960 and had said he wanted to coach the team into
the next decade. He did not return telephone calls to his home
Saturday.
   The NFL owners must approve the sale to Jones.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
