<FIRST>a a BC-WeeklyWallStreet Adv25-26   02-25 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Wall Street, Adv 25-26,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release weekend editions Feb 25-26</HEAD>
<HEAD>Inflation, Interest Rates Jolt Stocks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The latest round of bad inflation news and
interest-rate increases caught stock market investors with their
guard down.
   The 0.6 percent rise in the consumer price index for January
reported on Tuesday didn't come without any advance warning.
   After all, figures issued earlier had shown a 1 percent increase
for the same month in the producer price index of finished goods.
   And the Federal Reserve's move Friday to raise its discount rate
from 6.5 percent to 7 percent had been discussed on Wall Street for
months as a likely possibility.
   Indeed, some analysts had thought the Fed might raise the rate
charged on loans to private financial institutions to 7.5 percent.
   Yet stocks sold off sharply on both developments in Wall Street's
rockiest week so far in 1989.
   The problem, analysts said, was that the news hit at a time when
increasing numbers of investors were embracing the idea that the Fed
was on the inflation case and would have it successfully resolved
before long.
   Money managers who had formerly been taking a cautious, defensive
approach found themselves drawn into a new performance race as stock
prices rose and they chased after the market with buy orders.
   The biggest risk began to be perceived as being ``underinvested''
in a rally, rather than the perils of a declining market.
   As The Bank Credit Analyst, a forecasting firm, put it before the
storm hit, ``bond and stock market investors are not prepared for
another turn of the credit screws.''
   Now, the latest rate increases have raised some new questions, or
at least reemphasized some old ones: Can the Fed restrain inflation
without inflicting some significant pain on the economy?
   Or is that an impossible mission, like saying you are going on a
diet and hoping to lose 15 pounds without cutting down on any of
your favorite foods?
   ``The challenge facing the Fed is to tighten policy enough to
calm inflation, but not enough to send the economy into a
recession,'' said Jack Lavery, research chief at Merrill Lynch &amp; Co.
   ``The unpredictable delay between monetary tightening and a
slowing in economic activity makes that more difficult.''
   The extent of the new worries was readily event in the past
week's market numbers. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials
closed Friday at 2,245.54, down 79.28 points from the week before.
   The New York Stock Exchange composite index fell 4.73 to 161.72;
the NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market dropped
7.23 to 399.96, and the American Stock Exchange market value index
was down 4.46 at 321.49.
   Volume on the Big Board averaged 154.03 million shares a day,
against 156.85 million the week before.
   The inflation data for January, of course, tell the story for
just one month, a notoriously unreliable time span from which to
interpret trends.
   Some observers were quick to point out that the data probably was
skewed by temporary factors, even maybe the weather.
   But Alan Greenspan, the Fed's chairman, plainly took them
seriously, calling the report on consumer prices ``disturbing.''
That made it pretty hard for anyone else to shrug them off.
   ``We don't expect any slowdown in these kinds of figures for some
time,'' declares the current issue of the Merrill Lynch Market
Letter.
   ``Increasing pressures for inflation and interest rates indicate
the long expansion of the U.S. economy will run out of steam in the
second half of this year.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for weekend editions Feb. 25-26.</NOTE>
