<DOCNO> AP890225-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 0304EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d f PM-EconomyRdp     02-25 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economy Rdp,0577</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interest Rate Hikes Batter Stocks, Bonds</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For Saturday PMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Increases in key lending rates by commercial
banks and the Federal Reserve triggered the biggest stock market
setback in three months and sent bond prices lower.
   In the stock market, the Dow Jones industrial average skidded
43.92 points to close Friday at 2,245.54. It was the biggest daily
drop since November.
   In the broader market, seven stocks fell for every two that rose
among issues listed on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Bond prices lost as much as $4 for every $1,000 in face value,
sending interest rates higher with yields on 30-year bonds climbing
to 9.18 percent from 9.14 percent late Thursday.
   Short-term interest rates finished even higher: one-year Treasury
bills were yielding 9.50 percent late Friday, offering investors a
powerful incentive to dump stocks.
   The dollar finished mixed in foreign exchange trading.
   Gary Schlossberg, senior economist for Wells Fargo Bank in San
Francisco, said he expects interest rates will move even higher
before the economy slows enough to relieve inflationary pressures, a
goal the Fed has set for itself.
   ``The Fed will will have to continue to tighten a bit more
aggressively. A modest interest rate increase on the order of one
percentage point should be enough to cool the economy off
sufficiently,'' he said.
   Such a move would increase chances that the economy could fall
into a recession, another worry for stock investors trying to divine
the outlook for corporate profits.
   But, Schlossberg said, he believes ``the economy has enough
inherent strength'' that there is a better than even chance a
recession will avoided.
   Before the stock market opened Friday, the Federal Reserve
boosted its discount rate, its charge on loans to member banks, by a
half percentage point to a three-year high of 7 percent.
   Boosting the discount rate is the central bank's most dramatic
signal that it intends to tighten credit and slow economic growth,
thus reducing borrowing, wage and price demands.
   Some analysts said the Fed's move was overdue, especially in
light of Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan's statements that
he found recent inflation ``disturbing'' and that the bank would
continue erring on the side of retraint in fighting it.
   Fears about accelerating inflation have heightened in recent
weeks with news that wholesale prices shot up 1 percent in January
and that consumer prices were up 0.6 percent last month, their
biggest jump in two years.
   Until Friday, the central bank's moves had largely been conducted
behind the scenes, such as the draining of reserves from the banking
system, a maneuver that forces some banks to borrow to meet capital
requirements.
   The discount rate hike followed Chase Manhattan Bank's
announcement after the stock market closed on Thursday that it was
boosting its prime lending rate, a benchmark lending charge that
affects rates paid on commercial, home and other consumer loans, to
11{ percent from 11 percent.
   Other major banks matched Chase's increase on Friday. It was the
second half percentage point rise in the prime rate in the last two
weeks.
   The Fed last raised the discount rate in August, to 6.5 percent
from 6 percent. The discount rate last was at 7 percent from March
7, 1986, to April 18, 1986, when it dropped to 6.5 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890225-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-25-89 0531EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-CommuterAirlines Adv28   02-25 0723</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Commuter Airlines, Adv 28,0750</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tuesday, Feb. 28 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Can Pacific Northwest Support Two Major Commuters?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASCO, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``Help Wanted'' sign inside the beat-up
airplane hangar that serves as headquarters for United Express
announces openings for mechanics, accountants and pilots.
   It symbolizes the rapid growth of the Pasco-based airline
challenging Horizon Air for dominance in what has become one of the
country's hottest airline competitions, the struggle for the Pacific
Northwest commuter business.
   The fierceness of the competition is illustrated in the
Yakima-Seattle route, where passengers have a choice of seven direct
flights on United Express or eight on Horizon Air each business day.
   Officials for Horizon and United Express insist the skies over
the economically prosperous area are big enough for two airlines,
but Horizon has been feeling the heat in markets like Yakima, served
by both.
   ``Horizon essentially has negative growth,'' said Bill Whitlow, a
stock analyst for Dain Bosworth, Inc., a Seattle-based securities
firm. ``That was a result of United Express.''
   Horizon President John Kelly believes the competition is boosting
overall airplane ridership in the Northwest.
   He noted Horizon's slight increase in passengers from 1.38
million in 1987 to 1.39 million in 1988, despite United Express
boardings of 363,206 passengers during its first full year of
operations.
   ``They offer a good product and we offer a good product,'' said
John Beacham, director of marketing for United Express. ``It
encourages flying.''
   Unlike other airline competitions, however, passengers have not
benefited from any fare wars. A roundtrip cost for the 20-minute
flight from Yakima to Seattle is pegged at $130 to $178 for both
airlines, depending on discounts.
   Whitlow said that reflects the relatively equal competitive
standing of the two airlines, and their strong ties to larger
carriers.
   United Express is affiliated with United Airlines, which is No. 1
in the Seattle market and No. 2 in Portland. Horizon is owned by
Alaska Air Group Inc., No. 1 in Portland and No. 2 in Seattle,
Whitlow said.
   Neither has to cut fares to attract customers, he said.
   There is no question that Seattle-based Horizon has been feeling
the heat.
   In Yakima, its boardings dropped from 52,112 in 1987 to 40,022 in
1988, according to Yakima airport manager Gary Robbins.
   That decline can be attributed to United Express' 23,320
boardings in Yakima, Robbins said.
   ``We have been profitable in Yakima from the first month of
operation,'' Beacham said.
   ``The Northwest has some very good customer service, compared to
other parts of the nation,'' he said.
   Indeed, outposts like Moses Lake and Pullman, Wash., Lewiston,
Idaho, Kalispell, Mont., and Coos Bay, Ore., enjoy regularly
scheduled air service on at least one of the commuters.
   Horizon, formed with a Seattle-Yakima route in 1981, is much
larger, with 41 aircraft serving 30 cities in Washington, Oregon,
Montana, Idaho and Utah. It has 1,400 employees, compared with about
400 for United Express.
   Already spread into many smaller communities in the Northwest,
Kelly says the carrier is considering expansion into California,
where it would provide feeder traffic for Alaska Airlines flights in
San Francisco and Los Angeles.
   United Express, on the other hand, serves 13 cities in
Washington, Oregon, Idaho and Montana, and its expansion plans
center on breaking into Horizon's markets.
   One of five commuter airlines across the country that fly under
the marketing name owned by giant United Airlines, United Express is
owned and operated by WestAir Holdings Inc., of Fresno, Calif.
   United owns no equity in United Express, but the commuter is tied
in with United's reservation and frequent flyer system and fare
structure, and the planes are painted with the same colors.
   United Express's main mission is to feed passengers from smaller
communities to United's jet operations at Seattle, Portland and
Spokane, Beacham said. The company also plans to serve Boise, Idaho.
   Started in July 1987 with one Jetstream 31 19-seater flying from
Pasco to Seattle, United Express now has 16 Jetstreams and has
ordered eight 30-passenger Embraer Brasilia jetprops in a $48
million deal.
   For both airlines, the hottest battle is probably the
Seattle-Portland shuttle run.
   United Express offers 20 roundtrips per day and plans to up that
to 23 in March. Horizon offers over 30 flights between the cities
most days.
</TEXT>
